<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hiroshima Survivor Urges Pakistan to Avoid More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A survivor of the atomic bomb
dropped by the United States on the Japanese city of Hiroshima in
August 1945, Sunday urged Pakistan to avoid more nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Yasuhiko Taketa along with two members of Gensukin (Japan
Congress Against Atomic and Hydrogen Bombs) arrived in Karachi,
Pakistan's southern port city, Sunday and will fly into Islamabad
Monday, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
They will meet with Pakistani personalities, members of
non-governmental organizations, human rights groups in Islamabad,
Lahore and Karachi during their stay in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Taketa visited India and called on the Indian leaders
not to test any more nuclear devices and urged all atomic powers
to get rid of their nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
"You cannot bring about security with nuclear weapons and if we
continue testing nuclear weapons, we will not live much longer,"
Taketa told reporters in Bombay before departure for Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"The people of India and Pakistan must realize how terrifying
nuclear weapons really are. It will be difficult to make
governments accept this, but we cannot just sit around. Time is
too short," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
