<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian Exporters' Society will organize the
first exhibition of Jordanian industrial products in Algeria from
September 29 to October 2, Jordan's official news agency reported
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will provide Jordan's industrial companies with
chances to promote export to the North African country and boost
bilateral trade exchange, sources of the society said.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Jordan and Algeria in 1997 stood at
22.6 million Jordanian dinars (about 31.9 million U.S. dollars) in
favor of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Arabia has agreed to allow the
International Gulf Bank and banks of the other five members of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) to open branches in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the GCC Secretariat said the Saudi
decision came after a similar step by the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
Oman has also allowed the Manama-based International Gulf Bank
owned by all GCC members to open a branch in the country.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has decided to cut oil output by 20,000 barrels
per day as of July 1 in concerted efforts with other oil producers
to help shore up the world oil prices, the Egyptian Alam Al Yom
daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdi Al Banbi said Egypt will cut the
output from 850,000 to 830,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Iraq has decided to import 150 million dollars worth
of food from Egypt in the fourth phase of the oil-for-food program
signed between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili has
expected Egypt's export to Iraq to reach 200 million dollars this
year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's trade volume in the first quarter of 1998
stood at 14.8 billion Egyptian pounds (4.35 billion dollars), 1.6
billion pounds (471 million U.S. dollars) more than in the same
period of 1997, the Egyptian Al Ahram daily said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A report released by the Egyptian Central Authority for
Mobilization and Statistics said that Egypt's imports amounted to
2.4 billion pounds (558 million dollars) in the first three months
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudanese Minister of Civil Aviation and Survey
Hamid Mohamed Ali Torain has announced that Sudan will build a new
international airport in Khartoum, the official Al Anbaa daily
reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The airport, which is estimated to cost 750 million dollars,
will be built 25 kilometers east of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Torain said three foreign companies have submitted offers to
build the airport and the outcome of the negotiations with one
company would be announced next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
