<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Urges Oil Consumers to Import More Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) Sunday urged oil-consuming nations to refrain from adopting
protective policies on oil imports to secure the mutual interests
of oil producers and consumers, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
GCC Assistant Secretary General Abdullah Alkhleefi told a press
conference held in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia that oil producers would
suffer heavy losses if oil-consuming countries impose protective
laws on oil imports.
</P>
<P>
Alkhleefi said the GCC states are keen on keeping the easy flow
of oil supplies to the world markets, in tandem with other
producers and consuming nations to safeguard the growth and
stability of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
GCC, a regional political and economic alliance, comprises
Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain and the United Arab
Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states have managed to cut their daily oil output by
more than 1 million barrels since March in an effort to stabilize
the global markets and shore up prices.
</P>
<P>
Alkhleefi called on all producing nations to cooperate in
further reducing oil production to strengthen the oil prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
