<HEADLINE> Burundi Factions Agree to Cease Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 21 (Xinhua) - Leaders of the Burundi
government and all the opposition factions agreed in Arusha,
north Tanzania Sunday to cease fire, a report reaching here said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to begin the cease-fire process till July
20th when the second round of peace talks will start in a bid to
realize the national reconciliation and end years of bloody
conflicts in the tiny central African country.
</P>
<P>
A joint declaration by the 17 parties said six committees will
be established to deal with the problems of genocide, refugees,
peace and public security in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We will create a climate of lasting peace in our country and
bring to an end the constant cycle of violence and fratricidal
killings which have afflicted Burundi for a long time," said the
declaration.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between feuding factions in Burundi have been
sponsored by J. Nyerere, former President of Tanzania in order to
reach reconciliation and avoid sanctions imposed on the military
regime of P. Buyoya who assumed power in a coup in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were slapped on Bujumbura in August, 1996 by
east and central African states supported by the Organization of
African Unity and the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Appoints Impeached Interior Minister as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- In a move against the challenges of
the conservatives, Iranian President Mohammad Khatami Sunday
appointed impeached Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri as vice
president in charge of development and social affairs.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was announced by the official news agency IRNA
hours after Nouri failed to gain a vote of confidence from the
conservative Majlis (Parliament) which accused him of creating
tensions in the country, delivering provocative statements and
using inexperienced persons for managerial positions.
</P>
<P>
At the Majlis open session Sunday afternoon, 137 Majlis
deputies voted for a no-confidence motion against Nouri while
117 voted against the motion and 11 deputies abstained.
</P>
<P>
The new appointment indicated Khatami's strong support for
Nouri and his uncompromising stance toward the challenges of
the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Khatami and his moderate supporters have strongly supported
Nouri. Soon after 31 Majlis deputies called for an impeachment
against Nouri, they warned that Nouri's absence from the cabinet
would be detrimental to the government.
</P>
<P>
So far, Khatami did not announce any nominee to replace Nouri
as the interior minister. But the moderates have suggested that
Khatami choose Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, a former interior minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
