<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grenades Fired Toward U.S. Embassy in Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Three rocket-propelled grenades
were fired toward the U.S. embassy in Beirut on Sunday, causing
no human and material losses, the National Broadcast Network radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at 13:00 local time (1000 GMT) when no
diplomats were in the U.S. embassy.
</P>
<P>
The grenades landed only 500 meters away from the embassy on
the edge of Beirut, the radio added.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese security forces have found part of the time device on
the scene and launched investigation.
</P>
<P>
The press official in the U.S. embassy refused to make any
comments on the incident, saying only that Lebanese police would
deal with it.
</P>
<P>
During Lebanon's 1975-1990 sectarian civil war, Americans had
become targets of kidnapings and murders. A total of 241 U.S.
servicemen were killed in a suicide bombing in Beirut in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. lifted a 10-year ban on its citizens from
visiting Lebanon last July, it warned that the country was still
unsafe.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said the firing of the grenades was aimed at
undermining the stability of Lebanon which is seeking to project
an image of security to the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique, Malawi Step Up Border Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A few border counties of both
Mozambique and Malawi are taking concerted measures to strengthen
the good-neighborly relationship between them, the Mozambican
News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of local governments from Malawi recently paid a
visit to Mecanhelas County of Mozambique's northern Niassa
Province, and the two sides held friendly talks on matters of
their common concern along the border.
</P>
<P>
Magistrate of Mecanhelas County Domingos Vumbuca was quoted as
saying Sunday that the magistrates of Machinga County and Zomba
County led the Malawian delegation which included officials of
the departments of immigration, geography and land registration,
as well as some chiefs.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian delegates discussed with their Mozambican
counterparts about the prevention of epidemics, cholera in
particular, border security, cracking down on criminals, illegal
taxation and cattle rustling.
</P>
<P>
Domingos said both sides agreed to strictly observe the
regulations on passing through the border so as to resolve the
above-mentioned issues.
</P>
<P>
The officials from both sides also called for citizens of both
nations to condemn and tell on the trouble-makers along the
common border.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have worked out common strategy on sensitizing
local residents to sanitation so as to curb the spread of cholera
in the border area.
</P>
<P>
The local officials of the two countries have also decided to
increase exchanges of sports teams, and hold joint sports games
during festivities to cement friendly ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian magistrates proposed that the next meeting be
held in Malawi, but without giving a date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
