<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow Thunderstorm Leaves Six Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A powerful thunderstorm and blasts
in Moscow Saturday night left six people dead and 122 injured, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Official sources at the Moscow Mayor's Office said that more
than 45,000 trees were fallen, roofs were torn away from 300
houses, 744 breaks of power lines and 585 breaks of the contact
wire were registered.
</P>
<P>
Besides, many garages and cars were damaged, and advertisement
boards fell. The commuter train traffic was harmed.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the damage, done by the unprecedented
hurricane, will be estimated later.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the mayor's office, the wind with a
velocity up to 31 meters per second and 35 millimeters of
precipitation created an emergency in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The emergency measures were taken and the repair teams were put
on the alert and provided with all the machinery necessary, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
All the city services are working to repair the damage but
"greater forces and means" are necessary to fully eliminate the
hurricane aftermath, the sources at the Ministry for Emergencies
were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The gale Saturday night affected 20 towns in the northern,
north-eastern and eastern parts of the Moscow region, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
It said several districts did not have water supply, the
purification facilities and the sewage ran out of operation, while
the traffic of commuter trains was stopped by blockages in the
Dmitrov direction.
</P>
<P>
The most difficult situation is in the Podolsk, Mytishchi and
Shchelkovo districts, according to information from the Ministry
of Emergency Situations.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, the Itar-Tass said that the thunderstorm in
Moscow Saturday night did not cause any direct casualties.
</P>
<P>
Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov Sunday instructed full restoration of
the city by Monday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
