<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Jerusalem Plan Change No Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said Sunday that the controversial expansion plan of
Jerusalem will not change the status of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
The plan is only aimed at strengthening the economic basis of
Jerusalem and does not have any political indications, Netanyahu
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the plan does not violate the peace accords signed
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The plan, approved by the Israeli cabinet in the day after a
five-hour debate, would extend authority of Jerusalem to areas
surrounding the city by setting up an "umbrella authority" over
eight West Bank Jewish settlements to the east, south and north of
the city.
</P>
<P>
The United States has called the plan "a provocative step at
the sensitive time" in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and
urged Israel to reconsider it.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Sunday denounced the
plan as a new attempt to destroy the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Tibi, senior advisor to PNA President Yasser Arafat,
told Israel Radio that by adopting the plan Israel will annex
large part of the occupied territories of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the plan is a serious violation of the peace
accords between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace agreements, neither side should take unilateral
actions over Jerusalem before a final peace agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled since March
last year when Israel began construction of a Jewish settlement in
the traditionally Arab East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want
as the capital of their future independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
