<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Denounces Israel's Jerusalem Expansion Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister for
Development Jawad Anani Sunday issued a statement to denounce the
Israeli government's plan to expand Jerusalem's municipal
authority over eight Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Jordan strongly condemns Israel's plan to "expand Jerusalem,
annex new lands to it to be under Israeli control, annex the
settlement territories and build new tunnels and roads to link the
settlements, in addition to building an industrial complex for
technology," Anani, also the foreign minister, said in his
statement.
</P>
<P>
Jordan condemns the plan because it forms an open aggression
against the Palestinian territories and an open violation of the
agreements already signed with the Palestinians, according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government holds that Israel should be fully
responsible for this "provocative" decision and considers it to
be null and void, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government urges the Israeli government to stop
these measures because they are anti-peace and hindering the
whole Middle East peace process, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government also calls on the U.N. Security
Council and other international and regional organizations to
repulse these measures, Anani added.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which was approved after a five-hour debate in the
Israeli cabinet, would create an "umbrella authority" over West
Bank settlements surrounding Jerusalem to the north, south and
east.
</P>
<P>
It intends to put the settlements under the city's authority
mainly for building and planning.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured East Jerusalem in 1967 and later annexed it in
a move that has failed to win international recognition. The
Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of their future
state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been deadlocked for 15
months over Israel's settlement building in East Jerusalem and
long-delayed withdrawal from the West Bank. Israel has rejected a
U.S. initiative on further redeployment, which was accepted by the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the two Arab countries which signed peace
treaties with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
