<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Factions Agree to Cease Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 21 (Xinhua) - Leaders of the Burundi
government and the opposition factions agreed to cease fire in
Arusha, north Tanzania, Sunday, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The parties concerned have agreed to a truce not later than
July 20 when the second round of peaceful talks is called up in a
bid to realize the national reconciliation and end years of
bloody conflicts.
</P>
<P>
A joint declaration made by the 17 parties said that six
committees will be established to deal with the problems of
genocide, refugees, peace and public security and others.
</P>
<P>
"All armed parties to the conflict (agree to) declare a
suspension of hostilities to take effect not later than the 20th
of July 1998," the declaration said. "(We) pledge to resolve the
Burundi conflict through peaceful means, and to put an end to all
forms of violence."
</P>
<P>
"We will create a climate of lasting peace in our country and
to bring to an end the constant cycle of violence and fratricidal
killings which have afflicted Burundi for a long time," it said.
</P>
<P>
Concluding their week-long talks, first of its kind since
Pierre Buyoya took power of the tiny central African country two
years ago, some 50 leaders and representatives of the parties
committed to return to Arusha in July to start the second round
of talks facilitated by former Tanzanian president Julius
Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to put on the agenda the issues like nature of the
conflict and genocide in Burundi and their solutions,
constitutional and judiciary arrangements, public security and
permanent cease-fire arrangements, refugees rehabilitation and
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
The agenda also includes the economic and social
reconstruction and development, transitional institutions as well
as guarantees on implementing the agreements emanating from the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The parties also agreed to adopt at an appropriate time a
submission from facilitator Nyerere that will spell out the
methodology, time frame, organization and administrative
arrangements and rules of procedure.
</P>
<P>
"These will deal with, particularly, issues of participation,
conduct of deliberations, code of conduct of participants,
organization of the secretariat, working languages,
communications and logistics," the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace talks began last Monday when Burundi
President Pierre Buyoya told the opening session at the Arusha
International Conference Center that his government would like to
hold talks with all the opposition factions in an effort to begin
the national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Under mediator Nyerere, the talks brought together Burundi's
President Buyoya and leader of the main Hutu rebel group Leonard
Nyangoma, for the first time in a public forum since Nyangoma
fled the country in 1994 to join the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
Among the Hutu rebel groups at the talks were Nyangoma's
National Council for the Defense of Democracy (CNDD), the
National Liberation Front (Frolina) and the Party for the
Liberation of the Hutu People (Palipehutu).
</P>
<P>
Leaders from these groups, plus opposition FRODEBU, PARENA and
UPRONA and parliament made statements, saying that being tired of
the endless bloody conflicts, they hope all the factions should
shoulder the interests of the nation and the people, and seek
lasting solutions through sincere and serious talks.
</P>
<P>
Over the past week, Nyerere has been holding separate and
secret talks with all the parties in the five-star Novotel Mount
Meru Hotel and hosted an all-party talks finally.
</P>
<P>
"I hope all the main actors in Burundi will forget the past
and greet a bright future," Nyerere told the opening session,
which was attended by Presidents of Tanzania, Uganda, and Rwanda,
the Vice-President of Zambia and Kenya's Foreign Minister.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the U.N.
Secretary-General sent messages, saying that they were inspired
by the gathering of the Burundi leaders and promised support to a
real national reconciliation in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
As a gesture to answer the calls by sanctions imposers and to
ease the internal tension, Buyoya, an ethnic Tutsi, signed later
a new transitional constitution and named two vice-presidents
including an ethnic Hutu leader of the main opposition party.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in
bloody conflicts between the ethnic Hutu majority and the ruling
Tutsi minority since the assassination of Melchior Ndadaye, the
first president elected under a multi-party system in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
