<HEADLINE> Roundup: Iranian President Fights Back Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- In a move to counter the challenges
of the powerful conservatives, Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Sunday appointed impeached Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri as
vice president for development and social affairs.
</P>
<P>
The immediate appointment was considered as Khatami's reaction
to the no-confidence motion against Nouri by the Majlis
(Parliament) dominated by the conservatives and support for the
disgraced official.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said in a decree that he appointed Nouri to the new
post for the reason of his competence and ability, and the
importance of sustainable social and political developments.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-one conservative Majlis deputies raised a no-confidence
motion against Nouri on June 10. They accused him of creating
tensions, delivering provocative statements and supporting Tehran
Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi, who is on trial on graft charges.
</P>
<P>
At a Majlis open session Sunday, 137 Majlis deputies voted for
the no-confidence motion, 117 against it and 11 abstained.
</P>
<P>
At a cabinet session in the afternoon after the Majlis session,
Khatami praised Nouri for his efforts to maintain the country's
security and stability and push forward political reforms.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will surely continue to use Nouri's ability and
experience, he said.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the Majlis for the no-confidence motion at an
improper time, but saying that he and his government respect its
decision.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the conservatives raised the impeachment motion,
Khatami and his moderate supporters showed strong support for
Nouri. They warned that Nouri's absence would be detrimental to
the government.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that despite of the failure to save Nouri's
position as interior minister, Khatami managed to keep him in the
cabinet, giving him a free hand to continue his efforts to promote
social and political developments by supervising the affairs of
the interior ministry without conflicting with the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, Khatami has made it clear that he has the
responsibility to keep his promises made during the presidential
election campaign in May last year that he would promote freedom
and civil rights defined in the country's constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
