<HEADLINE> HK Launches Homepage for licensed Hotels on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Home Affairs
Department Monday launched a new Internet homepage which would
provide a user-friendly guide for overseas visitors and members of
the public to choose hotels and guest houses of acceptable safety
standard.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Monday on the launching of
the homepage, Shelley Lau, director of home affairs, said overseas
visitors and members of the public can now easily identify from
the Internet the licensed hotels and guest houses in Hong Kong
which have registered with the Office of the Licensing Authority
(OLA) of the Home Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
"The database of the homepage will contain names and
particulars of 94 hotels and 660 guest houses which have fulfilled
the fire and building safety requirements under the Hotel and
Guesthouse Accommodation Ordinance and have obtained licenses from
the OLA," Lau said.
</P>
<P>
"Lodgers' personal safety will be enhanced if they choose to
stay in these premises," she added.
</P>
<P>
Lau said the homepage also helps promote licensed hotels and
guest houses and encourage operators of unlicensed establishments
to improve their safety standards to meet the licensing
requirements.
</P>
<P>
The homepage, in both Chinese and English, is set up with the
assistance of the Business and Services Promotion Unit. The
English version is linked to the Hong Kong Tourist Association
homepage for easy access by overseas visitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
