<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Limitation on Electromagnetic Exposure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on Monday
recommanded, on health grounds, limitation of the exposure of the
general public to electromagnetic fields.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, EU's executive body, noted in a draft
recommendation that there are concerns regarding the potential
effects of man-made electromagnetic fields.
</P>
<P>
As listed in the document, sources of such fields are power
lines, electric appliances, railway systems, broadcasting
equipment, cellular phone systems and radars.
</P>
<P>
These sources, however, are essential to modern life, said the
draft submitted to the EU council of ministers for adoption.
</P>
<P>
Their potential health hazards, especially by non-ionizing
radiation, include electric shocks, skin burns and negative
influence on human central nervous and cardiovascular systems.
</P>
<P>
To address these risks, numerous safety regulations have been
in place both at EU and EU member state levels, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The new recommendation, once adopted, is expected to provide a
framework on basic restrictions and reference levels, and ensure
the consistency of EU-wide health protection policies.
</P>
<P>
It will help EU's 15 member states to provide for detailed
rules on how the guideline will apply in their countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ogata Urges Regional Leaders to Help Solve Refugee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees Sadako Ogata has appealed to regional heads of state
to find a peaceful solution to the conflict in Guinea Bissau, as
fighting in the West African nation stretched into its third week.
</P>
<P>
"Already, many tens of thousands of men, women and children
have fled the capital (of Bissau)," Ogata told the presidents of
Guinea Bissau, Senegal, and Guinea in a letter dated June 19 and
made public here Monday in a UNHCR press release.
</P>
<P>
Ogata warned that the confrontation "could generate a major
humanitarian crisis."
</P>
<P>
The high commissioner appealed to all parties to find "a
peaceful and prompt settlement."
</P>
<P>
She also asked U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
Organization of African Unity Salim Ahmed Salim, the Economic
Community of West African States and the U.N. Office for the
Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs to help solve the refugee
crisis.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR said that it had no news of the almost 5,000 refugees
from Senegal who live in villages in the Cacheu region of northern
Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
Reports indicate that fighting has also broken out in this
region, where the Jolmete refugee camp is located.
</P>
<P>
"Immediate consequences could be famine, refugee outflow into
neighboring countries and threats to the safety of the 5,000
Senegalese refugees who have been living in Guinea Bissau since
1992," said Ogata. 
</P>
</TEXT>
