<HEADLINE> More Countries Recall Ambassadors From Belarus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States, Poland and Japan
joined the European Union (EU) on Monday in recalling their
ambassadors from Minsk because of a row over a residential complex.
</P>
<P>
Media reports reaching here said U.S. ambassador Daniel
Speckhard, his wife and three children are scheduled to leave the
Belarussian capital on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Japanese ambassador Shigao Natsui is to depart Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the ambassadors of Lithuania and Turkey
already left the former Soviet republic on June 19.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, ambassadors of EU countries officially informed
Belarus that they would leave on Monday after the government cut
off water and gas supplies to the residential compound and denied
access.
</P>
<P>
Only five EU countries have embassies in Minsk. They are
Britain, France, Germany, Greece and Italy.
</P>
<P>
The EU countries' move does not represent an end of diplomatic
ties with Belarus, said an Itar-Tass report. The embassies will be
headed by charges de affaires during the interim.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors accuse Minsk of violating the Vienna Convention
on diplomatic rights in asking them to move out of the posh Drozdy
complex to allow for plumbing work.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko, who also lives in
the complex, said repairs are needed to the houses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the EU is also asking Belarussian ambassadors to
return to Minsk to convey the EU's attitude toward the Belarussian
actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
