<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Promises Millennium Dome Not to Be Torn Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
Monday hailed the Millennium Dome which will provide the focus for
Britain's millennium celebrations as "too good to be torn down."
</P>
<P>
The giant structure for the millennium celebrations had been
built to last, not to be taken down as envisaged, he said while
visiting the Dome construction site in southeast London.
</P>
<P>
"This will be the most famous new building in the world in the
year 2000," he said of the giant building which is still under
construction in Greenwich close to the River Thames.
</P>
<P>
Blair also praised the workers for their "extraordinary" work
and "spectacular" efforts and said he was proud of them.
</P>
<P>
What had been a piece of derelict land a year ago had been
built "on time, on track and on budget," he told building workers
at a ceremony to mark the "topping out" of the structure, which
was still viewed by many Britons as a waste of money.
</P>
<P>
Blair first visited the site a year ago when it was an empty
space of reclaimed industrial wasteland in Greenwich. He gave the
green light to continue the project, originally devised by the
previous Conservative government.
</P>
<P>
Its budget is 758 million pounds (1.3 billion U.S. dollars), of
which 400 million will come from the National Lottery and the rest
from business sponsors and the entrance money paid by an expected
12 million visitors. The dome will open with a spectacular concert
on the eve of the millennium date, December 31 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
