<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pledges to Improve Trade Action Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUCHING (Malaysia), June 22 (Xinhua) -- China, at the Trade
Ministers Meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
Monday, committed itself to improving its individual action plan
(IAP) for trade and investment liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting which opened here Monday afternoon,
Long Yongtu, chief representative for trade negotiations of
China's Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Ministry, said
China has always underscored the importance of implementation and
improvement of IAP.
</P>
<P>
China, he said, regards IAPs as the major instrument to achieve
the goal of trade and investment liberalization and facilitation
as envisaged by APEC leaders.
</P>
<P>
Long said, "We have put in enormous efforts for this purpose
year after year. Under the revised individual action plan for this
year, China is committed to bringing its average tariff level down
to 10.8 percent for industrial manufactured goods by the year
2005."
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the opening-up schedule for services on
environmental protection and energy has been added to the new
action plan and in accordance with the Industrial Catalogue
Guiding Foreign Investment, China has reinstituted some
preferential policies which will allow imported equipment and raw
materials for foreign-invested enterprises to be exempted from
tariff and import VAT (value-added tax)," he added.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that in the days ahead, China will, in an active,
serious, pragmatic and responsible manner, continue to flesh out
and improve its individual action plan.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to submit the plan for leaders' review in
November according to the agreed schedule," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IAPs and collective action plans are one agenda discussed
on the first day of the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Long also said that over the past two years, APEC members, by
formulating, implementing and revising individual and collective
action plans, have successfully advanced the trade and investment
liberalization and facilitation process.
</P>
<P>
The ministers at Monday's meeting also deliberated on
electronic commerce, which Long said is a brand new subject and
China follows closely and attaches great importance to its
development.
</P>
<P>
"We are supportive of APEC's efforts in research and
cooperation in this area," he pledged.
</P>
<P>
He said that at the initial stage, China proposes that
exchanges of experience and policy dialogue be intensified so that
members could get a better understanding of E-commerce.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said China is hoping that APEC could actively
advance technical cooperation and assist developing members in
enhancing their capacity building.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the progressive approach on E-commerce will
help APEC members achieve common prosperity as designed by leaders
in the APEC Leaders' Meeting in Vancouver," he said.
</P>
<P>
APEC groups Australia, Brunei, Canada, China, Chinese Taipei,
Chile, China's Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia,
Mexico, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
