<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister Expounds on Sino-U.S. Relations (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tang noted that President Clinton's coming visit will be the
first by an incumbent U.S. president in the past 10 years. He said
the two leaders will engage in extensive and in-depth exchanges of
views on international and regional issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government attaches great importance to the visit,
said Tang. The two sides have completed extensive preparations for
the event with mutual visits and talks, as well as thorough
exchanges of views on increasing cooperation and exchanges between
the two countries in areas such as the economy, trade, energy,
environmental protection, science and education, culture, military
contacts and laws. The two sides have made positive progress in
related efforts, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides have engaged in cooperative efforts and
consulted extensively on wide-ranging issued including the
financial crisis in Southeast Asia, dealing with the South Asia
nuclear arms race triggered by India's nuclear testing, and other
major issues directly related to both global and regional peace,
stability and development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side sincerely hopes and believes that successful
mutual visits by the two presidents will further enhance mutual
understanding between the two nations, promote extensive exchanges
and cooperation, develop ties based on the three communiques and
the Sino-U.S. Joint Declaration, and help fulfill the goal of
establishing a strategic partnership oriented with the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Tang stressed that Sino-U.S. ties represent one of the most
important bilateral relationships in the world and as such should
fully consider the world as a whole and long-term strategic
perspectives for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The world continues to witness profound changes with peace and
development representing the themes of the times, said Tang.
</P>
<P>
"However, the world remains far from peaceful and many
unstable factors continue to exist," according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
China, the world's largest developing country, and the United
States, the largest developed nation, are permanent members
of the United Nations Security Council. He said the two nations
share broad common interests and shoulder important
responsibilities for maintaining world and regional peace and
stability, as well as promoting global economic development,
safeguarding the environment and addressing other major
issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
