<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister Expounds on Sino-U.S. Relations (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Closer ties are not only in the interests people in the two
countries, but also reflect the requirements of the times and
expectations of people throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Tang cited hope, opportunities and severe challenges in terms
of specific steps for consolidating and developing bilateral
ties. "The evolution of the international situation has expanded
common interests and provided us with a broad scope of
opportunities for development and cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Developing stable and constructive relations between China and
the United States will not only benefit the two peoples, but will
also contribute positively to maintaining world and regional peace
and security, and promoting both global and regional economic
development, said Tang.
</P>
<P>
During last year's U.S. visit, President Jiang Zemin and
President Clinton decided that the two sides would strengthen
cooperation in dealing with challenges and promoting world peace
and development, and committed themselves to the establishment of
a strategic partnership between the two countries, according to
Tang.
</P>
<P>
He said that steps the two sides have taken based in the
spirit include:
</P>
<P>
-- further expanding negotiations and cooperation concerning
major world issues;
</P>
<P>
-- maintaining and increasing high level visits and contacts;
</P>
<P>
-- promoting mutually beneficial economic and trade cooperation;
</P>
<P>
-- expanding exchanges and cooperation in the fields of energy,
environmental protection, science, education, culture and law;
</P>
<P>
-- strengthening ties between the armed forces of the two
countries;
</P>
<P>
-- developing all forms of people-to-people contacts.
</P>
<P>
Tang pointed to the new international situation and stressed
that a bright future exists for the development of healthy and
stables Sino-U.S. relations if the two sides scrupulously abide by
the principles specified in the three Sino-U.S. communiques,
promote mutual understanding and properly handle differences,
especially in terms of the Taiwan issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
