<HEADLINE> Text of Statement from German Soccer Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Following are the text of the statement
issued by the German Football Federation issued on Monday following
the violence in Lens which involved German fans:
</P>
<P>
"It was with dismay and incredulity that (German Football
Federation President) Egidius Braun, the delegation and the entire
team of Germany learned late on Sunday evening of the serious
disturbances that had occurred after the match between Germany and
Yugoslavia in Lens.
</P>
<P>
"Egidius Braun said 'Our deepest sympathy goes to the injured
policeman and his family. We can assure him and his family we will do
everything we can to help him immediately and directly, although we
hope and pray he will return fully to health.'
</P>
<P>
"The delegation of the German team, national coach Berti Vogts and
all players explicitly demand that state authorities finally and at
last take rigorous action against all those who commit acts of
violence and who abuse the popularity of football for their senseless
misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
"Before the match in Lens there were already concrete indications
that people whose names were recorded on a computer list as individals
who habitually commit acts of violence in connection with sport would
travel to France without tickets.
</P>
<P>
"For this reason Wilhelm Hennes, security chief for the German
Football Federation, urgently wrote to the authorities on June 19
asking them to take the necessary preventative action.
</P>
<P>
"The hooligans responsible for these misdeeds are declared enemies
of society who trample over the reputation of sport and Germany. These
people are criminals who should not be mentioned in the same breath as
the millions of fans who love football and who go to stadiums only for
the enjoyment of the game.
</P>
<P>
"For many years the German Football Federation has been introducing
a series of security measures and has been working closely together
with fan groups in order to overcome these weighty problems. We have
seen in stadiums that the atmosphere is overwhelmingly joyous and
positive but when these hooligans take these acts of violence outside
the stadium and further afield then, as is the case with any criminal
act, only the state security forces can be held responsible.
</P>
<P>
"The delegation and the team of Germany regret yesterday's
incidents all the more because the time they have spent in France so
far has been characterised by outstanding hospitality and a superb
cooperation with the police authorities." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
