<HEADLINE> "Shock" Needed to Shore up Oil Prices: Kuwaiti Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh
Saud Nasser Al-Sabah said here Monday that the world oil market
needs "a shock" to shore up the prices.
</P>
<P>
"A shock is what the (world oil) market might need because the
situation is very bad," Saud said before leaving for Vienna to
attend a meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) due on Wednesday. But he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is in the interest of OPEC states to reconsider
the announced output cuts, adding that the matter will be
discussed in the coming meeting.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC meeting is expected to discuss further reduction of
oil production of its members to help shore up the oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Mexico and Venezuela agreed early this month to
slash oil output by 450,000 barrels per day. Some other countries,
including Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Oman and Iran, have
announced to follow suit to cut oil output by 270,000 barrels per
day.
</P>
<P>
Oil producers reached an agreement in March to reduce oil
output in a bid to raise the prices. But it has failed to achieve
tangible results.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Kuwait is ready to make further cuts, the Kuwaiti
minister said that "if it will lead to an improvement in prices,
then what is the harm." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
