<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee Monday urged Pakistan to engage in dialogue with
his country to resolve all outstanding issues in accordance with
the Simla Agreement reached between the two countries 26 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported from Simla, a summer
resort in northern Himachal Pradesh where Indian President
Kocheril Raman Narayanan and the prime minister are having a
sojourn, that Vajpayee also cautioned Pakistan against
internationalizing the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
"With our common experience of colonialism in the subcontinent,
as a cautionary lesson, no attempt should be made to
internationalize problems in our region," Vajpayee was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
On economic sanctions imposed by the United States and other
countries following India's nuclear tests in May, Vajpayee said he
had never threatened retaliation against the United States but
asserted that his country would boldly face such punitive measures
and never compromise on its security.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post reported last week that Vajpayee said in an
interview with the paper that India could retaliate if the United
States "rigorously imposed" economic sanctions on his country.
</P>
<P>
The United States announced last week the details of sanctions
worth about 2 billion U.S. dollars.  
