<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister Expounds on Sino-U.S. Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) - Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan granted an exclusive interview with Xinhua News Agency
today and noted that successful mutual visits between Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Clinton will propel
steady and healthy Sino-U.S. relations towards the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"On the whole, despite twists and turns in recent years,
Sino-U.S. relations have improved and are moving in a positive
direction," said Tang.
</P>
<P>
He explained that people in the two nations share the common
aspiration for the development of relations between China and the
United States, and noted that the two countries share extensive
common interests and enormous potential for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government seriously violated the three
Sino-U.S. joint communiques in 1995 and to a great extent
obstructed relations by allowing a visit to the U.S. by Lee
Teng-hui.
</P>
<P>
"Past lessons should be drawn," said the foreign
minister, noting that the relations between the two countries
have since improved and developed due to the concerted efforts of
both sides. A major indication was the highly successful state
visit Chinese President Jiang Zemin paid to the Untied State last
fall.
</P>
<P>
"The decision the two leaders made during the visit to engage
in concerted efforts to establish a constructive Sino-U.S.
strategic partnership set the direction and framework for
Sino-U.S. relations in the 21st century," said the foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have proceeded in accordance with the
Sino-U.S. Joint Declaration by increasing exchanges and
cooperation in a variety of fields such as politics, economy and
trade, military contacts, law, energy and environmental
protection. The two countries have continued to make progress in
efforts to improve relations, said Tang.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Clinton will pay a state visit to China between
June 25 and July 3 at the invitation of Chinese President Jiang
Zemin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister Expounds on Sino-U.S. Relations (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I believe that successful mutual visits between Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Clinton will ensure
steady and healthy Sino- U.S. relations continue in the 21st
century," Tang said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that properly handling the Taiwan question is the key
to the sound and steady development of Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
"History tells us that properly handling the Taiwan question
will ensure the relatively smooth development of
Sino-U.S. relations. On the other hand, improperly handling
the question will lead to setbacks and quite possibly
retrogression in bilateral relations," said Tang.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister pointed out that the three Sino-U.S. joint
communiques put forward a correct guiding principle for dealing
with the Taiwan question. The U.S. government has made an explicit
commitment to observe the "one China" policy and abide by the
principles outlined in the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques,
while at the same time steadfastly refusing to advocate "one
China, one Taiwan" or " two Chinas", refusing to support the
independence of Taiwan or its efforts to join the Untied Nations
and other international organizations which are composed by
sovereign countries.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that strict adherence to the three Sino-U.S. joint
communiques and the principles in the Sino-U.S. Joint Declaration
will promote the sound and steady development of
Sino-U.S. relations," said Tang.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the two sides quite naturally hold
different views concerning various issues due to different social
systems, historical backgrounds, cultural traditions and economic
development levels.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of differences, our view centers on enhancing
understanding and reducing differences by engaging in equal
consultations on a mutually beneficial basis," said Tang.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if some differences cannot be resolved quickly,
common ground should be sought. He stressed that two sides
should not let differences become obstacles affecting the
development of relations between the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Sets Three Conditions for Marcos' Burial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- President-Elect Joseph Estrada
Monday set three conditions for the burial of former President
Ferdinand Marcos at the Manila heroes' cemetery on July 11.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference held here, Estrada, who would assume
office on June 30, presented to the media a copy of his letter to
Imelda Marcos, the widow of Marcos, which was dated June 21 and
outlined the three conditions.
</P>
<P>
The first condition set by Estrada bars both Marcos loyalists
and anti-Marcos elements from attending the burial which, Estrada
said, should "strictly be solemn and religious."
</P>
<P>
Marcos' remains shall be ferried directly to Villamor Air Base
and forthwith to the cemetery for burial, Estrada said in the
letter.
</P>
<P>
"There shall be no stops and no organized groups shall be
allowed along the route to the cemetery," he said, stressing he
will see to it that his order will be strictly followed.
</P>
<P>
The second condition is the limit on the number of people who
can attend the burial. Estrada said that only 50 members of the
immediate family of the Marcoses can be present.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a private affair of the Marcos family," Estrada
said, assuring the public that he would instruct the military not
to give honors to the late president.
</P>
<P>
The third condition set by Estrada is that "the rites should be
strictly religious in nature and no political statements shall be
made."
</P>
<P>
Estrada added that the media will not be given access to the
event so that the ceremony can be "as solemn as possible" and that
the event would not be used for political purpose.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that by finally laying to rest his mortal remains, the
decade-long turmoil over the (Marcos) issue will subside. We can
then face our uncertain future as a united nation," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president-elect assured that no government funds
will be used for the burial, saying this is a private affair which
should be funded by the Marcoses.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, it was reported that Marcos' remains will be taken
from his hometown to Manila by a C-130 cargo plane of the armed
forces while the Marcos family will be flown by a Fokker plane,
also of the Philippine Air Force.
</P>
<P>
Should the Marcoses decide to use government planes, Estrada
said, they will have to pay for the gasoline and for the use of
the planes.
</P>
<P>
Estrada's plan to bury Marcos was opposed by some opponents led
by former President Corazon Aquino. The anti-Marcos groups accused
Marcos of killing thousands of Filipinos and looting state
treasury.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos has expressed his opposition to the
burial. He has also ordered an investigation into who ordered the
construction of Marcos' grave at the heroes' cemetery.
</P>
<P>
Marcos fled to Hawaii, the United States, in a popular revolt
in 1986 and died there three years later. His remains were allowed
to be returned to the Philippines in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
