<HEADLINE> EU-Belarussian Relations Deteriorating: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Relations between the European
Union (EU) and Belarus further deteriorated after EU nations
withdrew their ambassadors from Minsk, an EU official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, said Lousewies van der Laan, spokeswoman for European
Commissioner Hans van den Broek, the European Commission, EU's
executive body, is behind the decision to withdraw ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation EU and Belarus are expected to continue dialogues
through the British presidency of the union or the troika -- the
current EU presidency plus its predecessor and successor, she said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the head of the European Commission's delegation
in Ukraine, who is also accredited to Belarus, would be refrained
from having any official contact with Belarussian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Italy, France, Britain, Germany and Greece were the five EU
countries that had ambassadors in the former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
But they called back ambassadors following the EU objection to
the cut-off of water and electricity supplies and phone services
to their diplomatic residences on the excuse of house repair.
</P>
<P>
The EU also alleged that the Minsk authorities refused to allow
EU ambassadors' vehicles to enter their residential complex.
</P>
<P>
These were against the Vienna Convention, EU officials said.
</P>
<P>
A written statement by the British EU presidency said the
Belarussian ambassadors in EU capitals would be requested to
return to Minsk, a step to convey in strongest terms the
disapproval of EU governments of the latest Belarussian actions.
</P>
<P>
Ties between the two sides began to sour since last November,
when EU decided to give no public recognition to neither the new
constitution nor the new parliament of Belarus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
