<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Former South African state
president P. W. Botha, 82, married 57-year-old legal secretary
Barbara Robertson in a small, informal ceremony Monday Morning at
his home in Wilderness, Western Cape.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was attended by about 14 guests, including
Botha's two daughters and his son, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Botha's wife, Elize, died a year ago. He was engaged to
Reinette te Water Naude, 46, but the relationship broke off a few
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Robertson was introduced to Botha at the launch of his
autobiography "Voice in the Wilderness" last year.
</P>
<P>
Botha was currently on trial for ignoring a Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) subpoena. The trial will be
resumed on August 17 at George regional court and a judgement is
expected on the next day.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, Botha faces a sentence of up to two years in
prison or a fine up to 20,000 Rand (3,700 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He was subpoenaed to testify before the TRC for hearings on
activities of the new defunct state security council, which he
chaired in the 1980s. 
</P>
