<HEADLINE> Israel Ready for Exchange of Israeli, Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Israel is preparing to return
the bodies of 40 Hezbollah guerrillas and to release other 60
Lebanese detainees in exchange for the remains of an Israeli navy
commando, Israel Radio reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the arrangement, which Lebanese sources said has
been finalized, the body of Israeli Sergeant Major Itamar Ilya
will be transported to Israel by a French military plane via
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The plane will then return to Beirut with the bodies of 40
Lebanese, and the 60 Lebanese detainees will be transported by
bus and handed over to the Lebanese government through the
International Red Cross (IRC).
</P>
<P>
Ilya was one of 12 Israeli navy commandos killed in an
abortive raid in South Lebanon last September. One of the bodies
Israel is expected to return is that of Hadi Nasrallah, son of
Lebanon's leading guerrilla group Hezbollah (Party of God) leader
Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah.
</P>
<P>
France and the IRC have worked to make an exchange deal among
Israel, Hezbollah and the Lebanese government. Israel Radio said
the exchange, which had been postponed several times, will
probably take place within the week.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
border from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is fighting to oust Israeli troops and their local
South Lebanon Army (SLA) militia allies from the zone.
</P>
<P>
Six Israeli soldiers and at least 10 SLA soldiers have been
killed in the zone since the beginning of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
