<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Committee on Bilingual Legal System Holds Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Committee on
Bilingual Legal System, formed under the chairmanship of the
Secretary for Justice Elsie Leung, held its first meeting Monday
to review progress made in promoting bilingualism in the legal
system.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up to advise the government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) on the long-term goal of
legal bilingualism and address the policy and practical measures
to facilitate the development and promotion of a bilingual legal
system, having regard to Hong Kong's status as a member of the
common law family and an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
Members of the committee include the chief judge of the High
Court, law scholars, an industrialist and representatives of the
public and various government departments.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the progress made so far in promoting bilingualism in
the legal system, the committee noted the contributions of a
number of committees, including the Steering Committee on the Use
of Chinese in Courts, the Legal Practitioners Liaison Meeting and
the Advisory Committee on Legal Education.
</P>
<P>
Looking to the way forward, the committee noted that the
Department of Justice has initiatives in four broad areas:
drafting of bilingual legislation, publication of legal
glossaries, preparation of bilingual legal documents and training
of government counsel in the use of Chinese in their work.
</P>
<P>
Proposals by the judiciary include facilitation of use of
Chinese in courts, such as organizing specially designed language
courses for bilingual judges and judicial officers; compilation of
a glossary of legal terms and phrases commonly used in courts; and
putting in place a translation program of judgments of the Court
of Final Appeal, the Court of Appeal and the High Court.
</P>
<P>
Members also discussed a number of issues to take forward
bilingualism in the legal system on a long-term basis.
</P>
<P>
These issues include accessibility and improvement of reference
materials and information for the promotion of bilingualism in
law; translation of important English judgments delivered in Hong
Kong and other common law jurisdictions; training of lawyers in
the use of Chinese in court proceedings; and training of law
students in the bilingual legal system and Chinese legal
vocabulary and Chinese language skills in law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
