<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economy Seen to Post Positive Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Despite the ongoing financial
crisis, the Philippine economy would register a positive growth at
the end of this year while the economy of neighboring countries
contract, the Philippines News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the optimistic forecast was made by the
Institute of International Finance (IIF) and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) in their latest studies.
</P>
<P>
IIF projected that the Indonesian economy may contract by as
much as 12.5 percent this year; Thailand, 7 percent; South Korea,
5 percent; and Malaysia, 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, on the contrary, is projected to post modest
but positive growth figures. It is forecast to register a gross
domestic product growth of 2 percent while its inflation rate is
expected to settle at 8 percent at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In a recent economic briefing, Philippine Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson said the Philippines is likely to be the only
country among those ravaged by the Asian crisis that is able to
show positive growth this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the crisis, the country's economy would be
driven by bullish exports. For the first four months this year,
the country's merchandise exports grew by 19.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
In its study report, IIF projected that Indonesia's exports
will likely shrink by 11.5 percent and Malaysia by 2.1 percent.
Thailand and South Korea are forecast to post modest exports
growth of 3.8 and 2.8 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines' GDP grew by 1.7 percent in the first quarter
this year as a result of the financial crisis and the El Nino
phenomenon. The IMF agreed that the 2.4-3.5 percent GDP target is
attainable.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, said the inflation rate in the Philippines
would rise to 10 percent at the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
