<HEADLINE> Israel Explores Possibility of Holding Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Requested by Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, a special committee of the Israeli government
Monday convened its first meeting to discuss the possibility of
holding a referendum on the next troop redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, hosted by Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi, was
attended by Communications Minister Limor Livnat and
representatives of the Prime Minister's office.
</P>
<P>
During the session, the participants explored the legal basis
for holding a referendum, as well as the length of time it will
take.
</P>
<P>
They did not reach any conclusion on these matters and will
meet again to continue the discussion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai Monday told
reporters in Jerusalem that it is not necessary to hold such a
referendum.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government's efforts should be focused on
advancing the peace talks with the Palestinians, which have been
deadlocked for more than 15 months.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to revive the peace process, the United States has
presented a proposal to both sides, which reportedly calls on
Israel to hand over 13.1 percent of the West Bank in the second
troop redeployment, in exchange for the Palestinian tougher
actions against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has accepted the
initiative formally, while the right-wing in the Israeli
government rejected it, citing that any withdrawal of more than 9
percent would endanger the security of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure from the U.S., Netanyahu said that he is
considering taking the pullback issue to the public as a way to
solve the dispute in his government.
</P>
<P>
However, PNA officials argued that Netanyahu is only using the
consideration on a referendum as an excuse to continue stalling
the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
