<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Warns Against Fascism in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
warned, over the radio Monday on the 57th anniversary of the Nazi
German invasion of the former Soviet Union, the threat of fascism.
</P>
<P>
Being "worried that not all are feeling the threat of extremism
in Russia," Yeltsin told listeners: "Our common duty ... is to
prevent the 'plague of the 20th century' from surviving."
</P>
<P>
National flags are flying at half-mast around Russia to
remember "those killed in the war, those tortured to death in
prison camps and those who died of hunger and deprivation."
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, extremism is surging in Russia and poisoning
youngsters, who are fascinated by military symbolism.
</P>
<P>
As Russia struggles to bring itself out of economic
difficulties and many people are left jobless, extremism is seen
rising in the country, with mounting reports of violence against
ethnic minorities and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Yeltsin laid a wreath at the Tomb of the
Unknown Soldier. And he urged his people not to "forget the bitter
lessons of history for which this nation has paid so dearly."
</P>
<P>
At least 26 million Russians were killed in the Second World
War. And some Western historians put the figure as high as 40
million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
