<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Biggest Party Insists on October 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's biggest party, the United
Nigeria Congress Party (UNCP), has said that the October 1 date
for the military to hand over to an elected civilian government
is still feasible and realizable.
</P>
<P>
The party also stressed its stand against the extension of the
transition program as suggested by the four other parties.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried on major national newspapers Monday,
the party said it strongly support the pronouncement by Nigeria's
new leader, General Abdulsalam Abubakar, to conclude the
transition program on October 1, 1998 as originally planned.
</P>
<P>
The party dissociated itself from the views credited to the
other four parties that the transition program be extended by
three-12 month.
</P>
<P>
It suggested that the governorship and presidential elections
be adjusted from August 1 to August 29, while governors and state
legislators be sworn in on September 21, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The party refused the demand of the four other parties that
results of the December 6, 1997 state assembly election and the
April 25, 1998 national assembly election be cancelled.
</P>
<P>
UNCP won by overwhelming majorities in both elections, but the
four other parties accused it of having government support and
complained of massive rigging.
</P>
<P>
The party described the demand as "the bad loser syndrome"
that "has plagued our attempts at democracy".
</P>
<P>
"Even the 1993 presidential election which was adjudged to be
'freest and fairest' during the regime of General Ibrahim
Babangida was attacked by losers as being fraught with massive
rigging, corruption, abuse of the office and several forms of
irregularities," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Reminding that the two elections have been passed as free and
fair by international observers, the party said the call for
their cancellation is "a ridiculous after-thought and an attempt
to draw the clock back in an otherwise successful implementation
of the Transition Program."
</P>
<P>
fter all, it said, before the death of late head of state,
General Sani Abacha on June 8, no parties have called for the
cancellation of the election.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's transition to civil rule program met a major setback
with the sudden death of Abacha, who until his death, was the
consensus presidential candidate of the five parties.
</P>
<P>
As part of his wide consultations on the way forward for the
transition program, the new leader Abubakar has summoned the
parties on June 13 for discussion.
</P>
<P>
When it was clear that the parties were divided on the way
forward, with UNCP on one side, and the four others on the other,
Abubakar ordered that the parties put heads together and come up
again with a common position.
</P>
<P>
But according to the UNCP's statement, the parties met for two
days on June 16 and 17 and failed to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The UNCP decided to discontinue further participation with
the four parties when it became evident that they were inexorable
in their call for the cancellation" of the elections, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the new leadership will make up its mind
on the transition program in early July, when June 9-July 7
national mourning for Abacha ends.  
</P>
</TEXT>
