<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Cameroun to Meet World Court on Bakassi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Cameroun will hold a
special meeting Wednesday with judges of the International Court
of Justice on the dispute between the two countries over the
Bakassi Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to enable the three parties to decide
on the next line of action to solve the dispute, the Nigerian
Tribune reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian delegation, which left Sunday for the meeting at
Hague, the Netherlands, has made preparations not only for the
meeting but also for the case proper, it said.
</P>
<P>
The world's top court had earlier ruled that it was competent
to rule in the dispute over the ownership of the peninsula. The
case was filed at the court by Cameroun four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The decision of the court which is empowered by the United
Nations Charter to adjudicate on differences among nations, is
definite, with no appeal.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, disagreements over Bakassi date
back to 1985 when the Western colonial powers met in Berlin,
Germany, to slice up the continent of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Nigeria and Cameroun have been involved in series
of disagreements which sometimes resulted in fierce fighting
between Nigerian soldiers and the gendarmes of Cameroun, leading
to casualties on both sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
