<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya, Tanzania Sign Agreement on Ship Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Tanzania are among 17
countries which have signed the Indian Ocean Memorandum of
Understandings on Port State Control in a bid to ban unseaworthy
ships from the region from January, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which will enforce port state control, is part
of efforts by Indian Ocean maritime countries to implement
International Maritime Organization (IMO) conventions seeking
cleaner and safer seas, a local press report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The IMO wants to establish regional cooperation in port state
control to prevent the sub-standard ships from sailing, harmonize
inspections and facilitate the exchange of information.
</P>
<P>
Once the agreement takes root, ships plying the region's
territorial waters will be inspected upon entry in any member
state port and issued with a certificate of seaworthiness valid
for six months, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Countries signing the agreement have also agreed to set up a
regional secretariat in Goa, India, and an information center at
Pretoria, South Africa for an interim period of two years from
January 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
