<HEADLINE> Tourism Shoots up in Southern, Eastern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Southern and eastern Africa
registered a 17.8 percent growth in tourist arrivals and 19.1
percent in receipts last year.
</P>
<P>
The regions are now widely recognized as leading tourist
destinations in Africa, with South Africa serving as both a
leading tourist destination and a big tourist market, the East
African newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe received 1.9 million tourists and made 250 million
Dollars from tourism, while Kenya received over 750,000 tourists
who brought Kenya about 502 million Dollars of incomes.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania received 359,000 visitors, from whom it made 392
million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, Botswana, Zimbabwe and Namibia have established
a cross-border tourist network, according to the press report.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has a similar program with Tanzania. More than 66
percent of the tourists visiting Tanzania each year pass through
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Last month, an international travel and tourism conference in
Arusha, northern Tanzania, resolved to promote regional and
cross-border tourism in eastern and southern African region.
</P>
</TEXT>
