<HEADLINE> Israel's Jerusalem Expansion Plan Draws Wide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Israel's newly adopted Jerusalem
expansion plan drew wide criticism inside and outside the Jewish
state.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet Sunday approved a plan that would extend
Jerusalem municipal authority over eight settlements in the West
Bank, which is seen as steps to unilaterally expand Jerusalem's
borders.
</P>
<P>
In its Monday editorial, Israel's influential newspaper
Ha'aretz said that "the plan almost certainly is intented to
create territorial continuity between Jerusalem and the Jewish
cities and settlements -- such as Ma'aleh Adumim and Givat Ze'eve
-- that today are the very heart of Palestinian territory."
</P>
<P>
"When the government approved this development plan, it, in
effect, helped Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu lay a land mine on
the road towards achieving regional peace," it said.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the scheme's transparency, the government has no
right to complain about the harsh criticism" by the U.S. and the
Palestinians, because they considered the plan as a violation of
the Oslo Accord, the editorial added.
</P>
<P>
The accord stipulates that the status of Jerusalem, holy to
Muslims, Christians and Jewishes, should be negotiated in the
final status. Before that, the two sides should refrain from any
unilateral actions to change the city's status, demographic
composition and other characteristics.
</P>
<P>
The PNA chief negotiator Saeb Erekat said Sunday night that the
plan "constitutes a declaration of war on the Palestinian presence
in Jerusalem," terming it a "racist, religious decision" which
seeks to "upset natural demographic development and Judaize
Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Sunday called the
plan a "provocative" step adopted at a sensitive time when efforts
are exerted to revive the long-stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The 22-member Arab League also blasted the plan, saying that
"such Israeli acts provoke both the Arab world and the
international community, raising concern over the future of the
Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been deadlocked since March
last year when Israel started the construction of a settlement in
the Arab East Jerusalem. Israel's intransigence over its troops
redeployment in the West Bank has worsened the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
