<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Africa Calls for Joint Campaign Against Weed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The East Africa Cooperation (EAC)
has asked its three member states of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda
to work out joint strategies to control the rampant water
hyacinth in Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
"Coordination of joint regional efforts remains the best
option in the control of water hyacinth menace," Magaga Alot, a
spokesman for the EAC, was quoted by Monday's East African
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
EAC's first-ever ministerial meeting on the weed is expected
to be held this week following a two-day meeting of experts last
week in northern Tanzanian town Arusha, where the EAC secretariat
is based.
</P>
<P>
At the Arusha meeting, experts noted that measures at the
national level by the three countries so far have proved costly,
time-consuming and ineffective.
</P>
<P>
The measures include the introduction of beetles by Kenya and
Tanzania, a planned use of toxic chemical by Uganda, which is
opposed to by the other two states, the proposed use of weed
harvesting machines by Kenya and numerous research projects.
</P>
<P>
However, efforts to rid of the weed have "shown only limited
success," said Alot.
</P>
<P>
"Since the spread of the weed and its infestation process is
borderless, regional coordination in its control and monitoring
is necessary if maximum results are to be achieved," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting recommended that a committee of experts, working
under the EAC, be formed to work out a common strategy to deal
with the water hyacinth menace.
</P>
<P>
Last year the World Bank agreed to allocate 77.6 million U.S.
Dollars to the three sister nations in a five-year project to
counter the weed which has choked the second largest fresh water
lake in the world.
</P>
<P>
Uganda, which is the most affected by the weed, has admitted
that all the methods it has applied -- a combination of manual,
mechanical and biological, -- have had limited success.
</P>
<P>
"Assessment by the government shows that the manual method has
had limited success hectare," said Dick Nyeko, coordinator of
water hyacinth control in Uganda's Ministry of Agriculture,
Animal Industry and Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The aquatic plant exhibits prolific growth. In Uganda, an
annual average productivity of 1,700 to 3,500 tons of the wet
vegetation has been recorded.
</P>
<P>
However, the use of mechanical methods to combat the weed is
"even more expensive," said Nyeko.
</P>
<P>
"It involves the procurement of machinery, repairs and
maintenance as well as the removal of water hyacinth from the
surface and haulage to dump sites," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to sources in the Lake Victoria Environmental
Management Project, Uganda has at least 70 of its fish landing
sites blocked by the weed, devastating the economy of the
lakeside regions.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania have agreed that the biological
control method, though slow to show results, could be more
effective and less costly in the long run if compared with the
other two methods.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Agricultural Research Institute (KARI), which is the
main government agency in charge of Kenya's water hyacinth
control, has applied both bio-agents and mechanical control
methods with limited success.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has given more emphasis to biological control through
the introduction of two weevil species in the genus of Neochetina
-- N.Bruchi and N.Eichhorniae and a moth -- which have been
identified as biological control agents.
</P>
<P>
The weevils were imported from west Africa in 1995 and bred at
Kibaha near Dar-es-Salaam. Some 22,700 weevils were released in
Mwanza and Mara bay in October last year and another 51,650 in
the following two months.
</P>
<P>
Sources said millions of weevils already bred along the coast
which will soon be released into Lake Victoria to feed on water
hyacinth weed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
