<HEADLINE> Iranian Former President Calls for Oil Output Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran's former president Hashemi
Rafsanjani Monday called on all oil producers to slash their
output to revive the sluggish international oil markets.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani made the call in a meeting with the outgoing Qatari
ambassador to Tehran Ali Abdulaziz al-Kuwari.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani urged the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) to formulate practical measures in its coming
meeting to curb the sagging oil prices, the Iranian official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Iranian President Mohammad Khatami and Saudi Crown
Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz had a telephone conversation and
called for coordination among OPEC members to deal with the
current depressed oil market.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Iran and Qatar, all in Gulf, are OPEC members.
</P>
<P>
The 11 members of the OPEC will convene Wednesday in Vienna to
explore ways to revive the sluggish oil market and further oil
production cuts are expected.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices tumbled to a nine-year low of below 12 U.S. dollars
per barrel in March, which forced OPEC and non-OPEC members to
slash their output by 1.6 million barrels per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
The sagging prices have so far caused tens of billions of
U.S. dollars in losses for the oil producers.
</P>
<P>
Oil experts predicted that the OPEC members need to further cut
2.1 million bpd to revive the ailing oil market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
