<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Holding Arab Summit on Israel's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad
Anani on Monday called for holding an urgent Arab summit to find
ways of countering the Israeli plan to strengthen its hold on the
disputed holy city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by reporters from Israel Radio, Anani denounced the
Israeli Cabinet's decision Sunday to extend Jerusalem's municipal
boundaries as an "invalid political decision intended to annex
Palestinian territories by illegitimate and unacceptable ways."
</P>
<P>
The convening of an Arab summit is necessary and urgent,
because the Israeli plan to annex Jerusalem is detrimental to the
Arab people and will be categorically rejected by all countries in
the Arab and Muslim worlds, Anani said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that the Israeli move would speed up
the holding of an Arab summit and this issue will top the summit's
agenda. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has been lobbying for
support for holding such a summit to confront the Israeli
intransigence in the peace process, but no agreement has been
reached due to differences among the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
"There is a consensus (in the Arab and Muslim worlds) that all
the red lines have been trespassed. The potentials of peace and
hopes of building a real and comprehensive peace that provides
security and good life for all the peoples in the Middle East are
gone, thanks to these invalid measures," he added.
</P>
<P>
Anani said the Israeli measures are considered invalid because
they unilaterally changed the borders of Jerusalem, whose status
should be settled through the Israeli-Palestinian permanent talks
under the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that "Jordan rejects categorically the Israeli
decision, and considers it invalid and literally non-existent."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Anani issued an official statement to denounce the
the Israeli plan to extend Jerusalem's municipal authority over
surrounding towns and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized the Arab East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967
war and has declared the whole city as its eternal capital, but
the Palestinians hope to establish an independent state with East
Jerusalem as the capital.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, the second Arab country that signed a peace treaty with
Israel, has been consistent in supporting the Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
The future of Jerusalem is one of the most sensitive disputes
that should be hammered out in the final-status talks between
Israel and the Palestinians. But the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process has been stalled since early 1997, when Israel began the
construction of a major settlement in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
