<HEADLINE> Cholera Epidemic Worsens in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The cholera situation in the
Somali capital is deteriorating when all international aid
agencies have pulled out their international expatriates from
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The evacuation due security reasons followed the temporary
abduction of the ten workers of the International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC) in Mogadishu in April this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued at Benadir Hospital in
Mogadishu which has the best quarantine facilities, the doctors
had complained about lack of medicines and rehydration supplies.
</P>
<P>
The doctors had threatened that they won't be able to continue
managing the cases of the suffering people whom they called
"neglected cholera patients."
</P>
<P>
The doctors also said that cholera and the other contagious
diseases such as the measles will remain hazardous and menacing
considering the very poor sanitation in the capital accompanied
by the non-chlorinated water supplies mainly from the shallow
wells.
</P>
<P>
Statistics issued by the hospital indicated more than 7,157
morbidity cases while the mortality had exceeded 275 since
January this year.
</P>
<P>
Forlanini Hospital, another one with quarantine facility in
Mogadishu, is also accommodating cholera patients at the rate of
ten per day.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Health Authority (JHA) of Mogadishu has opened a new
clinic in Forlanini Hospital to give free consultations to the
poor people.
</P>
<P>
At the moment people in the capital have started treating
their patients inside their houses in the residential areas since
the quarantines have nothing to offer them. They buy rehydration
solutions and other antibiotics from private chemists, thus
aggravating the spread of the disease since the public awareness
programs had also been stopped.
</P>
<P>
The JHA has appealed to the international community to come to
Mogadishu to assist the Somalis at this particular moment when
measles and cholera are victimizing the poor Somalis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
