<HEADLINE> German Soccer Officials Shocked by Lens Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- German Football Federation said on
Monday they was shocked by the latest violence by German fans in Lens
and called on the authorities to take rigorous action against the
hooligans.
</P>
<P>
"It was with dismay and incredulity that (German Football
Federation President) Egidius Braun, the delegation and the entire
team of Germany learned late on Sunday evening of the serious
disturbances that had occured after the match between Germany and
Yugoslavia in Lens," said a statement issued by the federation.
</P>
<P>
The statement added, "The delegation of the German team, national
coach Berti Vogts and all players explicitly demand that state
authorities finally and at last take rigorous action against all those
who commit acts of violence and who abuse the popularity of football
for their senseless misdeeds."
</P>
<P>
It said the federation had tipped the French authority on arrival
of the country's soccer hooligans in France and asked them to take the
necessary preventative action.
</P>
<P>
However, the federation emphasized that these violent hooligans
should be told apart from the genuine fans who enjoy the sport.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, "These people are criminals who should not be
mentioned in the same breath as the millions of fans who love football
and who go to stadiums only for the enjoyment of the game."
</P>
<P>
It said the federation regret Sunday's incidents all the more
becase the German squad has been welcomed with hospitality in
France.
</P>
<P>
French gendarme Daniel Nivel, married with two children, were now
still in a deep coma after being attacked reportedly by German
hooligans. 
</P>
