<HEADLINE> German Leaders Outraged at Hooligan Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Monday
expressed outrage at the violent riots of German hooligans in the
French city of Lens on Sunday which left a French policeman
fatally injured.
</P>
<P>
"It is really a shame for Germany," said Kohl, adding that
those responsible for the attacks should face trial as soon as
possible in either German or French courts.
</P>
<P>
According to French radio reports, the 44-year-old French
policeman was still in critical conditions on Monday after
suffering head injures during clashes with German hooligans after
Sunday's World Cup match between Germany and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel also sent a telegram to
his French counterpart Hubert Vedrine to condemn the attacks.
</P>
<P>
"I'm shocked by the violent riots of German hooligans in Lens,"
Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also expressed support for a swift crackdown on
the rioters, saying "we should not allow a handful of violent
criminals to torpedo the World Cup which is held in the spirits of
fairness and gentlemanship".
</P>
<P>
German head coach Berti Vogts was also quoted by German media
as saying: "I would rather Germany having been defeated by
Yugoslavia so that the French police official could still be
healthy."
</P>
<P>
Germany staged a dramatic comeback to snatch a 2-2 draw with
Yugoslavia on Sunday, earning a vital point to keep the leading
position in Group F.
</P>
<P>
Police said that some 20,000 fans arrived in Lens without
tickets on Sunday. Many of them went on rampage and clashed with
police before and after the match. About 96 people were detained,
some of them were believed to be neo-Nazis, German press reports
said.  
</P>
