<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cars Powered by Natural Gas Debut in Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Natural-gas-powered cars are making
their debut in some Chinese cities as part of the nationwide
effort to fight a pollution problem in urban areas mainly caused
by vehicle fumes.
</P>
<P>
A taxi company in Chengdu, capital of southwest China's Sichuan
Province, had 27 of its taxis equipped with natural-gas last year,
and a year's operation has shown that the new method reduces fuel
cost by one-half.
</P>
<P>
And, more importantly, the use of natural gas dramatically
reduced pollution caused by vehicle fumes. Many other taxi drivers
expect to have their cars transformed into using natural gas,
according to the taxi company's manager.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an, capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province, worked
out a plan to expand the use of natural gas on vehicles for public
transportation in the next few years. Fifty buses are being
converted to natural gas, and will be put into operation in
August.
</P>
<P>
The new technology, the brainchild of a Xi'an-based gas
bottling company of the No.4 Research Institute under China
Aerospace Industrial Corp., has made it possible to process the
key equipment -- bottles made of synthetic materials for
compressed natural gas -- for natural-gas-driven vehicles, after
four years of research.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists say that more than 60 percent of air
pollutants in urban areas are produced by vehicle fumes. So,
natural gas has become the favorite choice at a time when people
badly need a clean energy source to replace gasoline for vehicles.
</P>
<P>
China is also making efforts to find substitutes for natural
gas, and the Xi'an product is the latest effort. China has rich
resources of natural gas, and plans to pump 25-to-30 billion cubic
meters of onshore natural gas during the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an-based company will have been able to produce 100,000
gas bottles of the kind annually by the end of the century,
sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuzhou to Maintain Unemployment Rate Below Two Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Fuzhou, capital of east China's
Fujian Province, plans to maintain its 1998 unemployment rate
below two percent.
</P>
<P>
Plans call for the city to provide jobs for 60 percent of the
projected 50,000 people facing lay-offs during the year.
</P>
<P>
The local government effort to reach the target includes a new
large-scale project to mobilize the general public to assist
unemployed workers.
</P>
<P>
Many firms have relaxed age and cultural level requirements for
job-seekers and placed priority on hiring unemployed people.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 17 job fairs held over the past two months
have helped over 10,000 find new employment. Some 20,000 laid-off
workers attended the various fairs and over 6,000 found new
employment.
</P>
<P>
The city has also attempted to ensure the basic living
standards of unemployed workers by adopting policies urging local
governments, firms and the general public to jointly cover the
basic living costs for those in need.
</P>
<P>
The city adopted 29 related support policies in 1997 and has
successfully maintained the local unemployment rate below 1.2
percent, a level much lower than the national average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
