<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Export Technology Via Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) plans to link the nation's first
virtual technology export market to the Internet (MOFTEC) via the
"Made-in-China" commodity market net launched last month.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC has granted approval to over 2,000 businesses and
research institutes to display their technology on the online
"China Technology Fair" which will be introduced August 12 on the
ministry's official website, according to the China International
Electronic Commerce Center (CIECC), the server.
</P>
<P>
The organizer expects the site to offer some 3,000 technology
items.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that many Chinese companies and businesses have
the capability to export technology but are nonetheless often
perplexed by the lack of information, high costs, the lack of
sales channel and unclear market positioning.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC notes the vast potential to increase the export volume
for key technological products such as computers and
telecommunications, electronic and biological products which
currently account for a mere 5.3 percent of China's total exports.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the MOFTEC Science and Technology department,
host of the online fair, is placing great hope on the fact that
the electronic-business system will enhance the efficiency for
transmitting information and reduce the cost of data exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the "China Technology Fair", another
E-business project sponsored by MOFTEC, centers on reducing costs
while greatly expanding the market recognition of domestic
technology.
</P>
<P>
Foreign experts point out that E-business, a method of "deals
done via electronic mail", takes full advantage of a shorter trade
process and the prompt response from the market and customers.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Trade and Development Organization estimated
that the transaction volume for global E-business will hit 200
billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC has announced that all import and export businesses will
be required to apply to the CIECC for quota certificate by the
year 2000. The ministry completed extensive testing of an
application network in east China's Shandong province last
October, with assessment completed and the system accepted at the
end of May.
</P>
<P>
The CIECC, established in 1996, is China's sole nationwide
network for the E-business network for foreign trade linked to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
Various foreign companies have targeted the E-business market
in China. For example, IBM has focused its development strategy on
providing small- to medium-sized Chinese enterprises with
useful information technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
