<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Motorola Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin said today
that the Chinese government places high value on the coming visit
by U.S. President Bill Clinton and believes its will end in
complete success.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Gary Tooker, chairman of the Motorola
Inc. of the United States, Jiang described Clinton's state visit
from June 25 to July 3 as a major event in Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
He said many major American companies, including Motorola, have
contributed greatly to promoting the healthy development of the
relations between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Motorola is a world-famous multinational company
enjoying the smooth advancement of business in China.
</P>
<P>
The 21st century will focus on information, said Jiang, adding
that the Chinese government considers information technology as a
focus of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome Motorola and other multinationals to invest in
China and open more factories," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Tooker noted that Motorola will further accelerate its research
and development of new products in China and will at the same time
increase technology transfers.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Motorola is preparing to shift its northern Asia
center to Beijing in the near future fully indicates the company
pays great attention to business in China.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Peiyan, minister in charge of the State Development
Planning Commission, attended the meeting.  
</P>
