<HEADLINE> Chinese Oil Company Expands Overseas Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The China National Star Petroleum
Corp (CNSPC), the country's third largest oil company, has forged
cooperative ties with oil companies and research institutes in
over 60 countries.
</P>
<P>
CNSPC President Zhu Jiazhen said today that his corporation is
currently enganged in a number of international oil exploration
and drilling projects in the Gulf of Mexico, the North Sea, the
Sea of Japan, Russia and Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that the Sino-Japanese Geological Engineering Corp.
(SJGE), a CNSPC joint venture with a Japanese firm, is fully
operational. He noted that SJGE exports petroleum equipment to the
United States, Canada, South America and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The CNSPC has also joined Australian companies in the
exploration and marketing of coal-bed methane gas in Shanxi and
Shaanxi provinces.
</P>
<P>
Other projects include a joint assessment of Hedong coal-bed
methane reserves, a technical cooperation project with U.S. firms
for development of the Yakela Oil and Gas Field, and a joint
project with Japanese companies to appraise oil reserves in the
Songhuajiang River Basin and the Liaohe River Basin in northeast
China.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that the CNSPC is striving to achieve an annual oil
and gas production of 10 million tons by 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
