<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Set to Adopt Law on Doctors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China plans to standardize medical
practices nationwide by adopting a law governing the
qualifications of medical workers and related professional ethics.
</P>
<P>
The draft law on doctors was submitted to the Standing
Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) today for
deliberation during its third meeting which is scheduled to last
five days.
</P>
<P>
The draft law stipulates that the nation will introduce a
system for registered doctors who have passed qualification exams
organized by the health departments above the county level,
according to Zhang Xuwu, vice-chairman of the NPC Law
Committee. Zhang made the comment in a report to the Standing
Committee on preliminary deliberation on the draft law.
</P>
<P>
The proposed law bans individuals without required certificates
from offering medical services, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
In addition, doctors must strictly abide by professional ethics
and specific operating procedures, improve their skills and
protect the privacy of patients.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the draft law, all medical workers are
prohibited from seeking personal benefits when performing their
specified duties.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that adoption of the law will strengthen the crack
down on medical charlatans across the country who frequently
overcharge patients for ineffective treatment.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that numerous unlicensed medical workers
provide services in rural areas. The country's mass media
frequently publicizes civilian cases involving medical malpractice.
</P>
<P>
The 47-article draft law has be deliberated on two previous
occassions and is expected to be passed this time around,
according to NPC sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
