<HEADLINE> HK Tourist Figures Remain Down, Forecast Revised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- With no respite from the
economic turmoil in the region, tourism continued to suffer in May
with arrivals for the month totaling 778,000, down 20.3 percent
from May 1997, the Hong Kong Tourist Association (HKTA) said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Total arrivals for the first five months of 1998 were 3.77
million, down 23.4 percent on the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the HKTA has revised its forecast for 1998 to less
than 10 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest figures, HKTA executive director Amy
Chan said: "We are facing a situation where the prolonged economic
downturn in the region is deterring outbound traffic, while the
depreciation of their currencies continues to erode the price
competitiveness of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
She noted that the HKTA now expects tourist arrivals for the
entire year of 1998 to be about 6 percent down on the 10.4 million
recorded in 1997, "but much depends on how quickly regional
economies stabilize in the coming months."
</P>
<P>
Chan said that the current economic turmoil is making it
increasingly difficult to make accurate forecasts of visitor
arrivals. "We must continue to closely monitor the situation and
make adjustments according to the prevailing situation," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
