<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Developing in Lanzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Optimistic signs for foreign
trade of Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's Gansu Province,
include a steady increase of exports, the development of
export-oriented enterprises and its export product structure.
</P>
<P>
An official from the economic and trade commission of Lanzhou
said that last year the city's exports totaled 350 million
U.S. dollars. Subordinate enterprises of the city reported 31.35
million U.S. dollars of imports and exports in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Preferential policies were given to foreign-invested,
export-oriented enterprises to encourage foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
With the increase of enterprises which have the right to import
and export, foreign-invested enterprises contributed more to
export trade in Lanzhou. In 1997, foreign-invested enterprises
reported 30.19 million U.S. dollars of exports, up 101.3 percent
compared to the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Besides a steady increase in traditional exports such as
industrial products, Lanzhou has become an exports base for beer,
calcium carbide and light-industry machinery.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the export of industrial and electro-mechanical
products in Lanzhou was 123 million U.S. dollars, accounting for
35 percent of the total exports in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
