<HEADLINE> Romanian PM Calls for Better Ties With Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The relations between Romania
and Poland must be revived, Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile
said Monday on his departure for an three-day visit to Poland.
</P>
<P>
Poland is "the most important country" in Central and Eastern
Europe, Vasile said, in addition pointing to the fact that it was
accepted to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
However, the head of government said, Romania's foreign
policies in the past "have neglected relations with Poland, which
should be revived at both political and economic level."
</P>
<P>
For Romania, a Polish lobby would be "as efficient as any
Western lobby for being admitted to NATO," he said.
</P>
<P>
As about the Romanian-Polish trade ties, Vasile said they were
"below their real potential," and expressed the hope that his
visit to Poland would "consolidate the Warsaw-Bucharest axis."
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the volume of trade between the two
countries was about 200 million U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In Warsaw, Vasile is expected to meet his Polish counterpart
Jerzy Buzek, President Alexander Kwasniewski, the speakers of the
Polish Parliament and Deputy Prime Minister Leszek Balcerowicz.
</P>
<P>
In addition to his schedule for time together with members of
the Polish National Chamber of Commerce, his last day of visit is
dedicated to a business meeting in Cracow with local officials.
</P>
