<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Arrives in Greece on Cyprus Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. presidential envoy Richard
Holbrooke arrived here Monday for talks with Greek officials on
resolving the country's disputes with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, assigned to serve good office on the Cyprus issue,
is expected to talk with senior Greek Foreign Ministry officials
and possibly with Prime Minister Costas Simitis.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have long been at odds, as both sides claim
sovereignty over the Mediterranean of island Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since troops from Turkey, in
reaction to a Greek Cypriot coup in Nicosia engineered by the
junta then ruling Greece, invaded the north of the island in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots proclaimed their own state in 1983 but is
recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
On his schedule for Friday, the U.S. envoy is to attend the
graduation ceremony of the American College of Greece in Piraeus,
about 15 kilometers southwest of Athens.
</P>
<P>
The post of Holbrooke, who has recently won the nomination of
Washington's ambassador to the United Nations, will be reportedly
transferred to another U.S. official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
