<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: U.S. Business Leader Upbeat About HK's Future (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Frank Martin, president of the
American Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong (AmCham), said that Hong
Kong will be the first economy to recover from the current
economic crisis in Asia because it has many advantages over the
other economies in the region.
</P>
<P>
Martin, who was appointed president of the AmCham in December
1990, told Xinhua at his office that members of the AmCham have
full confidence in the competitiveness of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
The rule of law and the unrestricted flow of information, which
constitute the two most important factors for Hong Kong's
advantages over its competitors in the region, remained unchanged
after Hong Kong's return to China on July 1, 1997, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that prior to the handover there was much concern
about the fact that there would be changes in Hong Kong's legal
system. But nearly one year after the handover "the legal system
retains its function, just as it was prior to the handover,"
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
"We mentioned the legal system because this is the most
important factor why international business remains in Hong Kong,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
"I expressed overall satisfaction that Hong Kong's legal system
has been retained without any interference from China's Central
Government," he continued.
</P>
<P>
Martin said that there was also a great deal of worry about the
censorship of the media prior to the handover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
