<HEADLINE> Museveni to Pay Education Fee for His Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
will start paying the education fees for his children in August
if the parliament approves a bill seeking to withdraw state
funding for the children of the president in July.
</P>
<P>
Hope Kivengere, the president's press secretary, was quoted by
East African weekly as saying that the bill will only apply to
the present head of state and is not binding for future ones.
</P>
<P>
She said the president had indicated on several occasions that
he could and would pay for his children's education.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1995 constitution, the state should provide fees for
four biological or legally adopted children of the president and
vice-president up to university level.
</P>
<P>
To cut down on public expenses and government spending,
Museveni announced on June 6 that he would reduce numbers of his
foreign trips and in his State of the House address he reiterated
his willingness to pay for his children's education.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, who came to power in 1986 and is now in his
mid-fifties, has four children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>    Martin stated that there is no change of the American presence in HK and it continues to be very strong. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Obviously the foreign businesses were affected by the economic
environment, but most of the American and the international
businesses will take a long-term view rather than a short term
one," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"So, we do not expect to see many companies leaving Hong Kong
and actually we have seen many new companies coming to Hong Kong,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
There are at least 20 new companies which have joined the
chamber this year, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
"We do see some companies downsize their business because of
the regional economic crisis, but they said they would not leave
Hong Kong and the contraction has nothing to do with the handover
but purely because of the regional economic crisis," Martin said.
</P>
<P>
Because most of the companies in Hong Kong are responsible for
the business in the whole region, many of the companies were
exporting to Southeast Asia and these exports have declined very
sharply, some companies have no choice but to reduce their staffs,
he explained.
</P>
<P>
This is a short term phenomenon, Martin said. In fact, many
companies are seeking business opportunities for investment in the
region, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's stability has much to do with its close
relationship with the Chinese mainland, the responsible behavior
of the Chinese leadership that promised the renminbi will not be
devalued at this time, and the strong economic growth of the
mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
