<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two South African Players Sent Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- With just two days before
South Africa's crucial World Cup game against Saudi Arabia, coach
Philippe Troussier on Sunday dismissed two players from the team
and also threatened to quit himself, South African media reported.
</P>
<P>
Midfielders Brendan Augustine and Aaron Mokoena were dropped
from the team Sunday after breaking a curfew for the second
time. The two stayed out late Saturday at a nightclub in Vichy,
France, where they were camping, in defiance of a curfew placed on
the players.
</P>
<P>
Ten players went out on a late night drinking spree last
Saturday, the day after they had been beaten 3-0 by France in
their opening match, and were reprimanded by Troussier.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the dismissal of the two, Troussier said the team
was not mature and there were only five players "who do what is
required of them and do prepare themselves for the game."
</P>
<P>
"The players have a responsibility to the team and the country
and they have to respect that. As a coach it must be my job to see
that we do well in this World Cup, and I can not accept that they
break the rules," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a visibly upset Troussier said he had "had enough"
and just wanted to finish his tenure as coach.
</P>
<P>
"I have received the message back from South Africa that they
don't want a foreigner as coach. Perhaps it is time for me to go
now. Maybe then they can open the champagne," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am too small for South Africa who need a big name and
stronger coach. This is not for me," Troussier said.
</P>
<P>
The South African squad need a big win in their last Group C
match against Saudi Arabia in Bordeaux Wednesday to secure their
place in the knock-out phase of the finals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
