<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denies Arms-for-Oil Deal With Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela's office has denied a report that his country had
concluded a secret 300-million-Pound (500-million-U.S. Dollar)
deal to supply Libya with weapons and spare parts in return for
cut-price oil.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Telegraph of Britain said the deal was approved by
Mandela, raising fears that Libya's Muammar Gadaffi might acquire
details of South African chemical and bacteriological weapons
built up during the apartheid era, Business Day daily reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I know nothing about it," said Parks Mankahlana, Mandela's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana said he believed South Africa imported no oil from
Libya and relied mainly on Iran and, more recently, Saudi Arabia,
for supplies.
</P>
<P>
Business Day did not say when Mankahlana made the remarks.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Telegraph said the arms-for-oil deal was negotiated
by South African secret service officials. It gave no date for
the deal.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, South Africa would supply spare parts for
Libya's aging Mirage jet fighters and attack helicopters,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
South Africa had also held out the possibility of supplying
Libya with its advanced Rooivalk attack helicopters, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Any such deal would violate United Nations sanctions, imposed
to put pressure on Libya to surrender two Libyan suspects in the
1988 bombing of a Pan Am jetliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, in
which 270 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has long been defensive about ties with countries that
the West regards as sponsoring or encouraging terrorism. During
a visit by U.S. President Bill Clinton to South Africa in March,
Mandela said critics of his ties with Cuba and Libya should
"throw themselves in a pool."
</P>
<P>
Mandela visited Libya twice last October. He has vigorously
defended his loyalty to Gadaffi and urged an end to U.N.
sanctions against Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
