<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- An influx of AMP shares Monday
sent turnover on the Australian Stock Exchange to a record high of
3.6 billion Australian dollars (2.2 billion U.S. dollars), as a
rally in BHP helped the market to a firmer close.
</P>
<P>
Defying a weaker ending on Wall Street Friday night, the all
ordinaries index lifted eight points to 2,596.8 after spending
some of the day in negative territory.
</P>
<P>
National turnover leapt to 3.6 billion Australian dollars from
its last record of 2.6 billion Australian dollars struck when BHP
sold its stake in Foster's Brewing company in June last year.
</P>
<P>
The flood of stock came from newly listed insurance giant AMP
Ltd., whose volume totaled 333.2 million, over half total national
turnover of 620.7 million.
</P>
<P>
Shares from AMP customers who did not take up the offer to
exchange policies for stock were offered to the market Monday.
</P>
<P>
But the share price of the giant insurance house closed down 68
cents at 20.02 Australian dollars, with one stockbroker noting
that institutional investors were standing on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the all resources index outperformed the bigger all
industrials index, with diversified miner BHP lifting nearly four
percent on continued takeover speculation and stable commodity
prices.
</P>
<P>
BHP closed 48 cents higher on turnover of 3.85 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index lifted 10.7 points, or 1.04 percent, to
1,041.9 points.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index lifted 6.2 points, or 0.14 percent,
to 4,529.4.
</P>
<P>
Both sectors were up despite Wall Street's performance. On
Friday the Dow Jones Industrial Average slumped more than one
percent or 100.01 points to 8,712.87.
</P>
<P>
In other equity news, Coca Cola Amatil gained 27.2 cents to
10.52 Australian dollars after shareholders approved a plan to
spin off the company's European bottling operations and create a
separate London-based company.
</P>
<P>
Market leader News Corp. Ltd. lifted three cents to 11.33
Australian dollars and the preferred shares lifted two cents.
Publishing &AMP; Broadcasting Ltd. fell eight cents.
</P>
<P>
The banking index lifted 29.6 points, or 0.52 percent, to
5,705.4.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 15.4 points higher, or 1.43 percent, at
1,089.6.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion closed at 295.55 U.S. dollars compared with 293.75
on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
