<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, Australia Sign Agreement on IT Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and Australia signed
Monday a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) on information
technology (IT) co-operation, the Government Information Services
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Information Technology and Broadcasting
K.C. Kwong, representing the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), and Chief Government Information
Officer of Australia Glenys Roper, representing Australia, signed
 the MOU in Canberra Monday.
</P>
<P>
The MOU is the second bilateral agreement on IT Co-operation
that Hong Kong has concluded with other economies. The first one
was made with Canada last month.
</P>
<P>
"The MOU reflects the mutual interests of both sides to promote
co-operation and exchange on IT. It is a positive step in the
further development of the close and long-standing relations
between Hong Kong and Australia," Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
The MOU focuses on areas of mutual interest for co-operation
which both sides have identified, including the delivery of
government services online, multimedia and software applications
and products, electronic commerce, broadband networks and
applications, and Internet applications, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Australia is advanced in IT development and applications. The
signing of the MOU will enable Hong Kong to benefit from the
experience and expertise of Australia. This will in turn help us
maintain our lead in IT and foster the growth of the local IT
industry," said the Hong Kong official.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the two sides had worked out preliminary plans
for cooperative activities under the MOU. The MOU will be for a
period of five years initially but can be extended by mutual
agreement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
