<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 303 Children Rescued From Rebels' Hands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- As many as 303 Ugandan children
have been rescued from the hands of the rebels of Lord Resistance
Army (LRA) over the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Monday's New Vision daily said that 164 of the children were
handed over to the assistant district commissioner of Gulu
district in northern Uganda and the rest to the World Vision
trauma counsel center and the Gulu "save the children"
organization last week.
</P>
<P>
The handover of the children took place seven hours after the
rebels abducted 15 children from Layibi trading center, six
kilometers from Gulu town center, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said two rebels and a captive were killed when the
army ambushed the rebels who tried to sneak back into their
hideout.
</P>
<P>
Local residents saw some 130 rebels looted the trading center
of posho, soft drinks, chicken and clothes.
</P>
<P>
LRA rebels stepped up abductions as government army exerted
mounting pressure on them.
</P>
<P>
Many of the abductees are said to become rebels or rebels'
wives. Recently there are some reports of young rebels aged
between 10 to 18 attacking the vulnerable civilians in the north.
</P>
<P>
There has been a mounting demand from the society for
government to hold peace talks with the rebels due to the
increasingly rampant rebel activities, but the latter has not
shown any indication of change of attitude in that direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
