<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Springs Slow Leak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar sprang a
slow leak Monday as it waited for further directional cues from
offshore, particularly Japan.
</P>
<P>
The local currency, which closed here at 60.86 U.S. cents from
61.27 last Friday, remained hostage to the U.S. dollar/Japanese
yen exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"And the outlook is far from clear," Bankers Trust fixed
interest strategist Rory Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
Recent strength in the Australian dollar and the Japanese yen
is reliant on signs emerging in the coming days and weeks of
genuine reform of the Japanese banking system and economy.
</P>
<P>
Both currencies were buoyed by the combined U.S. Federal
Reserve and Bank of Japan support of the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
"The lack of any concrete news on a reform timetable over the
weekend has disappointed markets and has seen the yen heading back
up towards 140 against the U.S. dollar," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
There is little news on the domestic front this week to offer
the local unit direction.
</P>
<P>
At the close in Sydney the Australian dollar was buying 84.07
Japanese yen from 83.47 yen last Friday and 1.0946 German marks
from 1.0981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
