<BODY>
<HEADLINE> KEDO to Meet on DPRK Nuclear Reactors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Korean Peninsula Energy
Development (KEDO) will meet in Brussels next Monday to discuss
how to share the cost for building two nuclear reactors in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), a KEDO spokesman
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, the United States, Japan and the European Union,
which established the KPEDO in 1994 to help the DPRK develop
two light-water reactors in exchange for the nation's suspension
of suspected nuclear weapons program, will re-assess the
cost-sharing of building the two reactors, originally estimated at
a total of about 5.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, South Korea pledged to share 3.5 billion of the total
while Japan agreed to pay one billion U.S. dollars and the United
States promised an annual provision of 500,000 tons of heavy oil
to the DPRK until the 1,000-megawatt reactors are completed.
</P>
<P>
After the nuclear test by India and Pakistan in May, South Korea
fears that the DPRK will restore its suspended nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, the DPRK said it would resume its suspended
nulcear program as the United States failed to keep its promise to
provide the nation with light-water reactors.
</P>
<P>
Due to strong challenges from the Republic-led Congress which
had been hesitant to secure the budget for the heavy oil, the
Clinton governemnt recently said it would like to supply safety
equipment for the DPRK's reactors if South Korea shared the cost
of heavy oil.
</P>
<P>
However, South Korea ruled out the possibility of sharing the
cost of heavy oil because of the current financial crisis caused
by corporate bankruptcies and non-performing loans of financial
institutions late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
