<HEADLINE> Dollar Moves Higher Against Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar moved higher against
the Japanese yen in Tokyo Monday as senior financial officials
from the 17 countries and regions failed to satisfy traders with
the outcome of their meeting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 138.53-56 yen at 5 p.m. (local
time), up from 138.18-20 yen at 9 a.m., and from 137.10-20 yen late
Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
Market players were bearish for the yen because no concrete steps
for Japan to improve the health of its financial sector resulted from
Saturday's gathering in Tokyo of deputies of finance ministers and
central bankers from the Group of Seven (G-7) and Asian-Pacific
economies, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Instability in the financial sector was highlighted by talk that
the ailing Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan is in merger talks, which
sent its share price down to 62 yen during the day, shedding the
permissible 50 yen.
</P>
<P>
The yen garnered some cautious support during the day on news of
discussions being held about financial restructuring, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's upward momentum is somewhat limited due to caution
toward further yen-propping intervention, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
