<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Accelerates Residential Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, the largest
industrial center in southwest China, plans to invest 6 billion
yuan to build residential houses this year.
</P>
<P>
That figure is equivalent to the amount of investment for the
entire 1991-95 period, said Li Yingru, director of the municipal
Real Estate Administration.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing has lagged behind other parts of China in residential
construction, Li said. In 1992, the per capita living space in
urban districts of Chongqing averaged 5.2 square meters, ranking
it last among 35 large cities in China.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing has a population of more than 30 million.
</P>
<P>
Since the central government decided to abolish the decades-old
practice of welfare housing distribution, local government has
pooled funds of the state, enterprises and individuals to build
new houses.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, half of the urban residents in
Chongqing have bought their own houses. The amount of funds
collected from individuals totaled 5.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Steady growth in the property market has boosted the
development of the building materials sector. A group of cement
and porcelain plants and building materials markets also have
sprung up in recent years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
