<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Orders Police to Preempt Leftist Plan to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Monday ordered the Philippine National Police (PNP) to take action
to preempt leftist rebels New People's Army (NPA) from kidnapping
family members of the late president Ferdinand Marcos.
</P>
<P>
In a handwritten directive, Ramos ordered PNP Director General
Santiago Alino to provide security "to likely NPA targets as may
be warranted."
</P>
<P>
NPA spokesman Gregorio Rosal announced that several NPA teams
have been sent out to track down and "arrest" former first lady
Imelda Marcos, her son Ilocos Norte Governor-elect Ferdinand
"Bongbong" Marcos and other Marcos cronies, so they can be tried
by a "people's court" for alleged human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
The "arrest" order was made following a decision by
President-elect Joseph Estrada to bury the remains of the late
strongman at the heroes' cemetery.
</P>
<P>
According to Rosal, the Central Committee of the Communist
Party of the Philippines has ordered the formation of NPA special
units to carry out the operation against the Marcoses and their
cronies.
</P>
<P>
"This is to obligate them to answer for their responsibilities
to the thousands of victims of human rights abuses," Rosal said in
a statement sent to media outlets Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The NPA and other groups have opposed the burial of Ferdinand
Marcos at the cemetery reserved for heroes and soldiers who died
in line of duty.
</P>
<P>
Former president Corazon Aquino whose husband Benigno Aquino
Jr. was assassinated during the reign of Marcos, is spearheading a
multisectoral group opposing the burial of Marcos at the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
Ramos directed Alino to "ensure that all of this (threat) does
not disturb the inaugural on June 30".
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Alino told reporters that the PNP would beef
up the security of Imelda Marcos and her children if they would
request anew.
</P>
<P>
Alino said there was now a PNP security team protecting the
former first lady and her family as provided by law.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who has stood pat on his decision not to allow the
burial of Marcos at the cemetery, also ordered Philippine Army
chief Raul Urgello Monday to investigate the ongoing construction
of the burial site.
</P>
<P>
He said in a handwritten memorandum that he has not ordered the
construction of such a burial site at the cemetery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
