<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Has New Financial Supervision Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Japan on Monday handed supervisory
power over the nation's financial industry to a new watchdog
agency to make financial administration more transparent.
</P>
<P>
The new Financial Supervision Agency was set up under the
Japanese Prime Minister's Office following the series of bribery
scandals involving Finance Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
It will carry out inspections of banks, brokerage houses and
insurance firms, and is entitled to impose administrative
punishments on financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
To signal the agency's independence, Masaharu Hino, former
chief of the Nagoya High Public Prosecutors Office, was appointed
as head of the agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency, with the Securities and Exchange Surveillance
Commission under its jurisdiction, is expected to take the lead in
restructuring Japan's financial sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
