<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Industrial Center Narrows Scope of State-Owned Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The government of Harbin, capital
of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, plans to reduce the
proportion of state-owned assets in its industrial sector from 70
percent to 50 percent by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The move aims to invigorate the vitality of the state-owned
sector and cultivate a new aspect of economic growth, said Mayor
Cao Guangliang.
</P>
<P>
Because of its longtime heavy industrial base, Heilongjiang
Province has a higher proportion of state-owned industrial assets
compared with other Chinese provinces. A great number of
state-owned firms are bogged down in financial difficulty as a
result of poor management and unmarketable products.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises in the fields of basic industry, public utilities
and the lifeblood of the national economy will continue to be
funded exclusively or controlled by the state in the future, Cao
said.
</P>
<P>
The city will turn 100 key enterprises into companies and set
up five enterprise groups each with a sales value of 5 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The local government also will sell medium-sized and small
state-owned firms by stages. The first group of 123 state-owned
firms to be sold have been chosen.
</P>
<P>
While reducing the size of the state-owned sector, the city is
encouraging the development of the self-employed economy by
granting preferential treatment in terms of investment, taxation,
enrollment and land use. They are allowed to buy shares of, or
purchase, state-owned enterprises to expand their strength.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
