<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Tumble on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Share prices tumbled Monday on
the Singapore market amid concerns about the ailing Japanese
economy as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII)
shed 24.48 points to close at 1,098.45.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said blue chips suffered the heaviest losses in the
trading of the day.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also said a weakening Japanese yen dragged prices down
further in the afternoon as the Japanese currency slipped close to
139 to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Despite international pressure, Japan failed to unveil a set of
specific policies designed to boost the economy at the weekend G7
meeting, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the G7 nations in Tokyo over the weekend had
been expected to lead to some concrete steps to support the yen,
but the meeting produced little in the way of action except for
platitudes that Tokyo must act swiftly and decisively to
revitalize its economy and restructure its financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume plunged to 92.55 million units, valued at
253.79 million Singapore dollars (153.8 million U.S. dollars).
There were 233 falls against 59 rises while 295 other counters
remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
DBS Land continued to be the most actively traded stock as it
registered a turnover of 9.12 million units. SingTel was next with
8.83 million shares traded. Easyknit took the third place with
5.89 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Rothmans remained the top gainer of the day as it edged up 30
cents to finish at 11.20 Singapore dollars. F&AMP;N increased by 12
cents to finish at 4.62 dollars while ChemInd gained 10 cents to
end at 2.20 dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS F topped the losers as it declined by 90
cents to end at 10.00 Singapore dollars. UOB F lost 50 cents to
close at 5.20 Singapore dollars. DBS was next which shed 40 cents
to finish at 7.10 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
