<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Condemns Assault on French Gendarme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- International soccer governing body FIFA
on Monday condemned the "vicious, savage attack" that had critically
injured a French gendarme in Lens.
</P>
<P>
Keith Cooper, FIFA Director of Communications, said the Bureau of
the FIFA's World Cup Organizing Committee, would also hold an
emergency meeting Monday morning discussing the security problems
during the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
"The only thing we wish to say at this moment is to express
sympathy and thoughts to the victim, the gendarme, who was so
barbarically attacked yesterday by the people whose motive defied any
normal understanding."
</P>
<P>
Cooper said FIFA deplores "every active violence in any way
connected to any football match anywhere in the world."
</P>
<P>
He said FIFA would issue a statement after the meeting later on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
French gendarme Daniel Nivel was still in critical condition in a
university hospital in Lille after he was attacked reportedly by
German hooligans in Lens after the game between Germany and Yugoslavia
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Lens authorities said six fans, whose nationality was not
announced, were deported immediately by the French Interior Ministry
after the violence.
</P>
<P>
Ninty-six people were detained for questioning, of which 15 were
held pending further enquiries by local police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
