<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singaporeans Urged to Build Up Cash for Old Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPOE, June 22 (Xinhua)--Singapore's Central Provident Fund
(CPF) Board released a bulletin Monday which will enable its
members to build up cash for their old age and earn more higher
interest on their retirement savings within the CPF framework.
</P>
<P>
The Board said that from July 1, CPF members below age 55 are
allowed to transfer their CPF savings from the Ordinary Account to
the Special Account up to a cap of 40,000 Singapore dollars
(24,242 U.S. dollars) in their Special Account.
</P>
<P>
As in the current practice, CPF members who are of age 55 or
above can transfer their savings from the Ordinary Account to the
Retirement Account to receive higher interests and members do not
contribute to the Special Account once they reach age 55.
</P>
<P>
When the decision takes effect, Members' savings in the CPF
Special and Retirement Accounts will earn an interest of 1.5% per
annum more than their savings in the Ordinary and Medisave
Accounts, the board said. the interest rate for the CPF Special
and Retirement Accounts will be 5.9 percent for the period July 1
to December 31, 1998 as compared with the interest rate of 4.29
percent for the Ordinary and Medisave Accounts for the same
period.
</P>
<P>
The transfer of CPF savings from Ordinary Account to the
Special Account can be made at any time but will be subject to the
cap of 40,000 Singapore dollars in the Special Account, the Board
said.
</P>
<P>
The Board noted that CPF members' transfer of savings from the
Ordinary Account to the Special Account is not reversible. That
means a member cannot transfer his savings back from the Special
Account to the Ordinary Account subsequently when he needs it for
housing or investment.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's Central Provident Fund (CPF) was set up in 1955 to
provide financial security for workers upon retirement or when
they no longer work. Over the years, the CPF has evolved into a
comprehensive social security savings scheme that takes care of
members' retirement, healthcare, home ownership, family protection
and asset enhancement needs. Both the employer and employee
contribute to the fund. The monthly contribution rate for workers
aged 55 and below is 40 percent of the worker's salary, with equal
contributions of 20 percent from both employers and employee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
