<HEADLINE> Backgrounder for President Clinton's China Trip: U.S. Businesses Earliest and Biggest Foreign Investors in Xi'an </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- When the first jointly run
Sino-U.S. hotel, Golden Flower (now the Shangri-LA Golden Flower
Hotel), opened in this capital of northwest China's Shaanxi
province in the spring of 1985, it served as a window for locals
to have a view of the western life style. Today, U.S.-funded
businesses have become an important part of Shaanxi's economy.
</P>
<P>
American business people were among the first to invest in
Shaanxi, and the amount of their investment ranks only after that
of Hong Kong and Taiwan regions, leading all foreign investors,
according to the provincial foreign trade and economic department.
</P>
<P>
There are 277 projects with U.S. funding or participation in
the province, making up 10 percent of its Sino-overseas equity and
contractual joint venture projects. The total investment of the
277 projects reaches 456 million U.S. dollars, in which 112
million U.S. dollars are from U.S. partners.
</P>
<P>
The projects span machinery, electronics, medicine, chemical
industries and the entertainment business, and it is reported that
the rich mineral deposits in northern Shaanxi have become a new
point of interest for U.S. businesses.
</P>
<P>
Although Xi'an does not boast the same convenience in
transportation as China's coastal areas, its low labor cost and
good education system have been important factors behind the
success of Xi'an-Janssen Pharmaceutical Ltd., one of the best
Sino-foreign joint ventures in China, said Jerry Norskoj, former
Xi'an-Janssen general manager and now vice president for
development in China of the U.S.-based Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
<P>
Industrial experts point out that Shaanxi's geographical
location at the junction of central China and the vast western
region also helps attract overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Many investors agree that transportation and communications
facilities and policies for overseas investment in Shaanxi
Province have been substantially improved over the past two
decades since China first adopted the reform and opening-up policy.
</P>
<P>
To support economic development in the relatively backward
central and western region, the Chinese government has formulated
a succession of preferential policies for the region in recent
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
