<HEADLINE> Chinese Universities Brace for Modernization Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Preparing for the knowledge
economy era, China is carrying on an ambitious plan to modernize
its outdated colleges and universities in a bid to meet the
challenge of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education announced here today that some 60
universities have been selected in a national program to upgrade
college facilities and improve teaching systems. The program is
being called the "211 Project."
</P>
<P>
The project is the only educational item on a list of state key
construction programs for 1998, which contains 117 items.
</P>
<P>
The plan was drawn up in the mid-1990s by the Chinese
government to build 100 mega-universities which can reach the
heights of universities in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials say that 350 key specialties in the 60
universities will receive funds for renovation, and an educational
computer network and document system will be established to link
universities nationwide.
</P>
<P>
On the list are prestigious institutions of higher learning
universities like Beijing and Qinghua universities, and a large
number of provincial universities.
</P>
<P>
The University of Science of Technology for National Defense
has also been included in the "211 Project."
</P>
<P>
Sources say that these universities have imported more
equipment from overseas and set up advanced laboratories. Some of
them have strengthened themselves through merging with other
universities.
</P>
<P>
China's modern universities appeared in the late 19th century
and adopted the former Soviet Union model in the 1950s. Most of
them are poorly operated and students have no information about
the scientific frontiers, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The country is expected to invest more than 13 billion yuan
(1.57 billion U.S. dollars) in the project during the Ninth
Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), which is the largest investment
in the educational sector since new China was founded in 1949.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
