<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Trade Ministers Meeting Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUCHING, Malaysia, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The meeting of ministers
responsible for trade of Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
opened here Monday afternoon with a call for APEC to support
initiatives to deal with the financial crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
Opening the two-day meeting, Malaysian International Trade and
Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz, chairperson of the meeting, said
the meeting is being held during a period of financial and
economic turmoil in East Asia, constituent of the APEC region, and
at a time when the individual economies of East Asia are
struggling to keep afloat and to bolster flagging currencies and
depressed financial and trade markets.
</P>
<P>
She said, "The turmoil has triggered off various degrees of
economic crisis, impacting upon a broad spectrum of economic
sectors, and thereby effectively curtailing capacity to generate
economic growth."
</P>
<P>
Regional and global economic interlinkages and interdependence
will directly or indirectly spread that so-called contagion effect
to other economies outside the region, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Individual APEC economies experiencing the economic turmoil
must necessarily undertake domestic policy initiatives to effect
economic recovery. But it is also important that in the spirit of
APEC, other APEC member economies understand the problems and,
where possible, assist in the process of economic recovery," she
said.
</P>
<P>
"In fact it is in their interest to do so in order to prevent
the crisis turning into a full-blown Asia-Pacific and global
economic recession," she added.
</P>
<P>
Therefore this meeting cannot ignore what's happening in the
region, Rafidah said, adding "Our deliberations must be in the
context of diminished economic capacities of the affected member
economies."
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the ministers will take stock of the
progress of work, including on Early Voluntary Sectoral
Liberalization (EVSL), Individual Action Plans (IAPs), Collective
Action Plans (CAPs), Electronic Commerce and impact of trade
liberalization according to the agenda of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
On the EVSL, the ministers will review progress of work in the
15 sectors identified under the EVSL initiative, which are divided
into two groups.
</P>
<P>
The first group of nine sectors -- chemicals, environmental
goods and services, energy, fish and fish products, forest
products, gems and jewelry, medical equipment and instruments,
toys and telecommunications, mutual recognition arrangement, in
which work is expected to be completed by this year.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will also examine progress in the remaining six
sectors -- automobiles, civil aircraft, food, natural and
synthetic rubber, fertilizers and oil seeds.
</P>
<P>
For the IAPs which are in implementation for the second year
this year, members will report to the ministers at the meeting on
preliminary plan for improvement/new commitments including the
steps undertaken to implement existing IAP commitments.
</P>
<P>
As for the CAPs which cover a wide area comprising 15 trade and
investment sectors such as tariffs, services, investment, customs
and standards, the ministers will review these actions and assess
the outcomes achieved in facilitating trade and investment in the
APEC region.
</P>
<P>
Electronic Commerce is another area of emphasis for APEC in
1998 and the initial phase of the work program, that is, the
educative process, was undertaken in the first half of this year.
The ministers will decide on the next course of action.
</P>
<P>
The minister will also review the progress on work to promote a
broad-based and balanced understanding of the impact of
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the ministers will have a dialogue with APEC Business
Advisory Council (ABAC) on the collective response of APEC to ABAC
recommendations which contain requests for measures to further
liberalize and facilitate trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will consider also how APEC could make further
contribution to the World Trade Organization (WTO) in light of the
outcome of the Second WTO ministerial conference.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of all the APEC members -- Australia, Brunei,
Canada, China, Chinese Taibei, Chile, Hong Kong of China,
Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand,
Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and the
United States, are attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Three members-designate -- Peru, Russia and Vietnam as well as
observers from ASEAN, South Pacific Forum and the Pacific Economic
Cooperation Council are also present at the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
