<HEADLINE> NPC Standing Committee to Mull Drafts of Three Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature today
began deliberating drafts of three laws and other proposals and
reports, including the revised draft law on the village committee
organization, which will affect more than 900 million rural
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC), presided over the third meeting
of the NPC Standing Committee, which opened today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xuwu and Zhou Keyu, both vice chairmen of the NPC Law
Committee, separately reported the previous deliberations on the
draft laws on doctors, exclusive economic zones and continental
shelves. The two draft laws might be approved by the Standing
Committee at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Li Boyong, vice chairman of the Law Committee, reported the
preliminary deliberation of the revised Law on the Use of
Land. The NPC Standing Committee issued the draft law to the
public in the previous month. Until June 15, the Commission of
Legislative Affairs of the NPC Standing Committee had received a
total of 611 letters from the people about the law.
</P>
<P>
Doje Cering, Minister of Civil Affairs, explained the draft
revision of the Village Committee Organization Law. The proposed
law stipulates that village committees make public a list of the
village's assets, income, expenditures, land leases and building
permits.
</P>
<P>
Yang Wenchang, vice-minister of Foreign Affairs, explained the
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights and
an extradition treaty between the People's Republic of China and
Mongolia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
