<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Question Kenya's Cigarette Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's recent imposition of duty
on cigarettes from member states of the Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) has drawn protests from Tanzanian
cigarettes producers.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania Cigarettes Company (TCC) makers of Aspen and Club,
had expressed concern over the move, saying it had only two
percent of Kenya's market share, the East African weekly reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan cigarette market, long dominated by BAT Kenya Ltd.,
has just seen the entry of TCC and Philip Morris. But TCC is
"the only major exporter of cigarettes to Kenya among the COMESA
states," said TCC spokesman Bernard Palela.
</P>
<P>
He said the company's only option, if it wanted to continue
selling its products in Kenya, was to raise prices, in some cases
doubling them.
</P>
<P>
In an amendment of the Kenya Customs and Excise Order, which
came into force on April 1, 1998, a five percent duty available
in the COMESA area is imposed by Kenya on unprocessed tobacco and
tobacco refuse.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured cigarettes entering Kenya would be taxed at 300
Kenya Shillings (five U.S. Dollars) or seven percent per
kilogram, up from 30 Kenya Shillings (50 U.S. cents).
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan move is reminiscent of an incident last year when
Tanzania imposed heavy taxes on beer from COMESA countries, whose
largest brewery is in Kenya, while making it easier for
non-COMESA members to export beer to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
TCC's major exports to Kenya were Club and Aspen, which was
launched in Nairobi in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
Kenya does not export cigarettes to Tanzania because the
existing trade mark arrangements forbid such trade, according to
the East African report.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Kenya raised import duty on cigarettes from 30
percent to 35 percent and reduced VAT to 14 percent, only to
increase it to 17 percent shortly thereafter, with a COMESA duty
of 30 Shillings (50 cents) and excise duty of 135 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kenya and Tanzania are among the 24 members of COMESA which
succeeded the Preferential Trade Area (PTA) from eastern and
southern Africa and the Indian Ocean Islands of the Comoros,
Madagascar and Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
Under the COMESA Treaty, member states agreed to reduce tariff
rates on all products which qualify under the rules of origin to
zero by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 08:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Saudi Arabia Calls For Bolstering Oil Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Saudi Arabia have called
for more coordination among world oil-producing countries to
prevent further decline in oil prices, the Tehran Times reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-Saudi call was issued by Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami and Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz during a
telephone conversation Sunday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders focused their discussion on the coordination
among members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) in a bid to bolster the sagging oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Khatami voiced concern over the oil slump, saying an
appropriate step must be taken at the next OPEC session due to be
held in Vienna, Austria, on Wednesday. Prince Abdullah also
underlined the need for more coordination among the OPEC members
at the session, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
At the Vienna meeting, oil ministers of the 11 OPEC countries
are expected to explore ways to reduce their oil output as part of
the ongoing efforts to save oil prices from further fall.
</P>
<P>
Despite the intensive high-level contacts and pledges of the
OPEC members to further cut oil production, the oil prices
remained low.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the price for Iranian light crude plunged
below 10 U.S. dollars per barrel and the International Benchmark
Brent stood at about 12 dollars per barrel last week.
</P>
<P>
During the past weeks, Saudi Oil Minister Ali Naimi and
Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Zanganeh made whirlwind trips to the
Persian Gulf Arab states, lobbying for their support for further
production cuts.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Saudi Arabia, the two oil giants in the Gulf region,
have announced their readiness to cut production. They expected
that the Vienna meeting could reach a coordinated decision on
bolstering the oil prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
