<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Families Hiring Lawyers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Lu Huaiyang, an elderly man in
Nanjing was annoyed by his sons and daughters who were arguing
over his property.
</P>
<P>
To settle the dispute, Lu hired a private lawyer to serve as
his family adviser. Through a legal procedure, Lu prepared a will
to cover the disposition of his assets and end his children's
bickering.
</P>
<P>
Lu is just one of more than 200 families in Nanjing, capital of
east China's Jiangsu Province, who have invited lawyers to be
their legal advisers. In Nanjing, a city that took the lead in
restoring a system of lawyers, more and more families are now
consulting attorneys when they have troubles.
</P>
<P>
Duan Zhengkun, director of the Department of Lawyers of the
Ministry of Justice, said that the Chinese people are now fond of
legal procedures to handle their problems. Lawyers are becoming
popular not only among businessmen, but also among ordinary
citizens.
</P>
<P>
More than 11,000 families or citizens in the country have hired
lawyers in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
In China, it takes about 500-to-1,000 yuan per year for a
citizen to hire a lawyer to be a private legal adviser. For many
Chinese citizens whose annual income is 5,000 yuan (about 630 US
dollars), the expenditure is not high.
</P>
<P>
Most of the people hired lawyers not only for lawsuits, but
also for their knowledge of the law as it relates to domestic
affairs involving a division of assets, divorce agreements, house
sales and loan applications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Families Hiring Lawyers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing Weiheng Lawyers Office started its service in the real
estate business in September of 1997. It has served more than
5,000 clients.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiaowei, head of the office, said that in recent years
there has been more and more disputes between citizens and housing
project developers.
</P>
<P>
"To get their desired apartments in time, many of our clients
are turning to our office to seek legal aid so as to avoid some
unexpected troubles in their house dealings," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Nanjing, 62 lawyers' offices have opened private legal
services for citizens.
</P>
<P>
When Jinling Lawyers Office started its business for local
families this year, lawyers in the office were invited to serve 58
families within 20 days.
</P>
<P>
In the cities of Shenzhen, Shanghai and Guangzhou, more than
1,000 families and more than 50 percent of self-employed
households have hired lawyers.
</P>
<P>
In the rural areas in central China's Hunan and Hubei
provinces, some farmers hired lawyers as their legal advisers to
help them resolve their business disputes.
</P>
<P>
Duan Zhengkun said that with the perfection of the legal system
in China, the tendency to hire private lawyers is becoming
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
Since 1979, when China resumed the system, lawyers' offices in
the country now number 8,300 with 100,900 lawyers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
