<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 08:00 GMT, June 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Chart Pattana Party, one of Thailand's major
political parties, elected a new leader in its annual congress
held here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Korn Dabbaransi was elected new party leader to replace the
late Chatichai Choonhavan, who died of cancer on May 6.
</P>
<P>
Chart Pattana Party, the third largest political party in
Thailand, holds 52 seats in the 293-strong National
Assembly. (Thailand-Party-New Leader)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUCHING (Malaysia) -- The United States Monday asked Japan to
deregulate and open its economy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. made the appeal at the bilateral meeting between
Japanese International Trade Minister Mitsui Horiuchi and
U.S. Chief Negotiator Charlene Barshefsky before their
participation in the two-day APEC Trade Ministers Meeting which
opens here later Monday, a spokesman of the U.S. delegation said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. reiterated that "Japan must be the engine of growth
for Asia" and in addition to applying fiscal stimulating measures
in dealing with banking sector, Japan should deregulate and open
its economy, the spokesman said. (Malaysia-APEC)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Ignoring international pressure, Russia signed an
accord with India on Sunday for construction of two 1,000 mw light
water nuclear power reactors in Tamil Nadu, the southern state of
India.
</P>
<P>
The Times of India reported Monday that the accord, which is
supplement to a decade-old agreement with the former Soviet Union,
 was signed by visiting Russian Atomic Energy Minister Yevgeni
Adamov and Chairman of Indian Atomic Energy Commission
R. Chidamabaram.
</P>
<P>
The agreement for building two civilian nuclear power plants at
 a cost of 2.6 billion U.S. dollars was reached in 1988 between
former Soviet Union President Mikhail Gorbachev and the then
Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi. (India-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Opposition candidate Andres Pastrana
defeated ruling party candidate Horacia Serpa and won Colombia's
presidential run-off election, official from the National Registry
Office said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 97 percent of votes counted, Pastrana collected over six
million, or 480,000 more than his rival.
</P>
<P>
Upon his winning, Pastrana, 44, made a speech, reiterating his
platform promise of peace, reform and more
jobs. (Colombia-Election-Result)  
</P>
</TEXT>
