<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bronson Runs 47.03 Seconds in U.S. Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Bryan Bronson clocked a
brilliant time of 47.03 seconds, the third fastest 400-meter
hurldes ever, at the U.S. Athletics Championships in New Orleans
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Marion Jones won her third gold medal after clocking 22.24
seconds in the women's 200 meters to become the first athlete in
50 years by winning the golds in 100-meter, 200-meter and long
jump at the championships.
</P>
<P>
Three other season best marks in the world were produced today
at the three-day meet.
</P>
<P>
Bronson, 25, improved his personal best by a sizable six-tenths
of a second in the finals. His 47.03 run was only surpassed by
world record holder Kevin Young's 46.78 and Edwin Moses' 47.02.
</P>
<P>
"Coming down the stretch I was watching the clock. I saw 46
seconds and I hammered it," said the world bronze medalist.
</P>
<P>
"If the world record doesn't come this year, I've still had a
great season," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jones, who had won the 100m and long jump yesterday, said
following her 200m triumph:"My legs were tired. I was feeling
exhausted from three days in the heat, but to come out here and
survive and stay healthy was good enough for me."
</P>
<P>
Setting the year's best marks today were Kim Batten, who
clocked 53.61 seconds in the women's 400-meter hurdles, Jerome
Young, who hit the tape 44.09 in the men's 400 meters and Reggie
Torian, who edged Mark Crear with a 13.03 to win the men's 110m
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
Olympic and two-time world champion Allen Johnson didn't
compete in the hurdles, instead, he ran the 200 meters and
finished 20.54 to winner Gentry Bradley's 20.47.
</P>
<P>
Jeff Hartwig, who set the U.S. pole vault record with a 6-meter
leap, won the event at 5.85m, and Olympic high jump champion
Charles Austin cleared 2.30 meters to win the title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Currency Won't Be Devalued, MOFTEC Officials Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Senior Chinese officials
reiterated here today that the Renminbi (RMB), the Chinese
currency, will not be devalued.
</P>
<P>
Despite the huge pressure exerted by the drastic fall of the
Japanese yen on China's exports, the exchange rate of the RMB will
remain unchanged, said Sun Zhenyu, vice minister of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), at a press conference
organized by the Information Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng added immediately that the RMB
will not be devalued.
</P>
<P>
"Once again, on behalf of the Chinese government, I assure you
we are not going to devalue the RMB," he stated.
</P>
<P>
The stability of the RMB is the requirement for China's stability
and development, as well as for the prosperity and stability in
Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China is capable of maintaining the stability of the RMB," he
said, adding that China has maintained a foreign exchange reserve
of about 140 billion U.S. dollars since the end of last year and
has a gross trade surplus of 30 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
China gained a trade surplus of 17 billion US dollars from
January to May this year, and its economic growth rate reached 7.2
percent in the first quarter, when the Asian economy met with
difficulties. "This has given us confidence that we are able to
maintain the RMB exchange rate without devaluation," he said.
</P>
<P>
China is a big country, and it is determined to play a
responsible role at a time when the Asian economy has
difficulties, even if it has to pay a price for not devaluing its
currency, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"We believe it is very important for China to maintain a
responsible attitude and to play a role in stabilizing the Asian
economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that Japan, an economic
power in the world and an important country in Asia, will also
play a responsible role in the current difficult period.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen should also play a role in stabilizing the
Asian economy rather than playing a destabilizing role, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to see the governments of Japan and the United
States take resolute action to intervene in the situation and to
stop the further falling of the Japanese yen, Shi said, and serve
as a stabilizing force in the Asian economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
