<HEADLINE> Zambia to Restrict Work Permits to Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has warned
that it will not issue work permits to foreign companies and
organizations that prefer employing expatriates in positions
which can be competently handled by indigenous Zambians.
</P>
<P>
State-owned Times of Zambia Monday quoted Deputy Minister of
Labor Syacheye Madyenkuku as saying here at the weekend that the
Zambian government will not entertain situations where companies
and organizations deliberately bring in expatriates to take up
jobs which are not highly technical and exceptional in nature.
</P>
<P>
Except for highly skilled and technical areas such as medical,
financia and technological fields, no permits will be issued to
any company or organization applying for other jobs.
</P>
<P>
Madyenkuku emphasized that there are enough qualified Zambians
to take up jobs and therefore he did not understand why some
organizations insisted on bringing in their own people from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister disclosed that Zambia has a long-term
program to ensure that as many jobs as possible are manned by the
Zambians and the country will on "the basis of individual merits
be able to allow the employment of expatriates for short periods
of about three years."
</P>
<P>
In cases where work permits are issued, the company involved
is required to have a deliberate human resource development and a
study program to facilitate take-over by the Zambians, said the
deputy minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
