<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Australian Firms' Asia Plan Not Affected by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Asia's financial crisis was
having a limited effect on Australian companies, with only a
minority changing their business operations or their long-term
investment plans for the region, a new research report released
Monday showed.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 70 percent of the 40 major listed Australian
companies had either increased their business activities in Asia
or kept the status quo, a Macquarie Equities research report said.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Equities interviewed senior management from the 40
companies, taking in the sectors of alcohol and tobacco, building
materials, developers and contractors, mining contractors,
finance, food, diversified industrials, media, paper and
packaging, healthcare and biotechnology, transport, tourism and
leisure, and resources.
</P>
<P>
While some sectors such as tourism had been severely impacted
by the financial and economic upheaval in Asia, others like
insurance had increased their activities and investments in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"Since the crisis began, only five percent of companies have
substantially scaled back their operations and investments in Asia
(by way of subsidiaries, joint ventures and representative
offices)," said David Rickards, author of the report.
</P>
<P>
"A further 25 percent have scaled back operations only
slightly, leaving 70 percent having unchanged or increased
operations," he said.
</P>
<P>
A similar story emerges for long-term investment plans.
</P>
<P>
"Only around 10 percent of companies have substantially revised
their plans for the Asia region, with the remainder having
unchanged or only slightly different plans," Rickards said.
</P>
<P>
"While 70 percent of companies have reported a fall in sales
to Asia over the past year, only a quarter reported that sales
have fallen by more than 25 percent," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, companies are confident that the long-run effect
on sales will be minimal; 75 percent believe that within two years
sales will equal or exceed the level prevailing before the crisis
(with 50 percent expecting higher sales); and less than three
percent anticipating much lower long-term sales," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said companies therefore had not felt the need to
push aggressively into other markets, with only a quarter seeking
greater sales from the U.S., Europe and other Asian countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
