<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Increases Domestic Oil Allocation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has ordered
an upward review of the domestic crude oil allocation from
250,000 barrels per day to 300,000.
</P>
<P>
This is in a bid to increase the petroleum product supply
nationwide and arrest the hydra-headed oil crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The order came just as Petroleum Minister Chief Dan Etete had
banned all refinery chiefs from travelling out of their stations
but to gear their efforts toward speedy repair of their plants.
</P>
<P>
The government also approved four multi-national oil companies
to engage in direct importation of fuel for current consumption
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Import of petroleum products is being done solely by the
governme-owned Pipelines and Products Marketing Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
No fewer than 52 cargoes of 30,000 tons or 39.75 million
liters each, have been imported by the company within the past 12
months to satisfy a national daily demand of 18 million liters.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the ministry Sunday did not specify the
companies involved.
</P>
<P>
There are now seven such companies operating in Nigeria on
behalf of the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation. They are
Shell, Mobil, Chevron, Agip, Elf, Texaco and Pan Ocean Oil.
</P>
<P>
In order to reduce direct import of the products, the
government is to undertake a long-term arrangement for offshore
processing of about 50,000 barrels per day of Nigerian crude oil
whereby deficit products would be brought back to augment direct
importation and local production.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has to import petroleum products because all its four
refineries are undertaking turn around maintenance and
rehabilitation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xi'an through the Eyes of Foreigners (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite obvious cultural differences, Linda S. Pickle, Coggin's
colleague, said she still feels at home here.
</P>
<P>
Before she came, she had read some books about China. And Xi'an
meant to her an old and underdeveloped city. After arrival, she
found that, in addition to the ancient architecture and ruins,
there are lots of beautiful shopping centers and up-to-date urban
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
It's a city of prosperity and vigor, representing the harmony
between tradition and modern development, Pickle said.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Bennett was motivated by his intense love of the Chinese
culture to come to Xi'an. The Stanford professor has spent two
years here. He speaks only a little Chinese, but knows a lot about
many ancient Chinese classics, including the "Art of War" by Sunzi
and the "Book on Changes." His favorite poets, Li Bai and Du Fu in
the Tang Dynasty, also lived in Xi'an, he said.
</P>
<P>
Many of his friends have come to Xi'an and were deeply
impressed, he said.
</P>
<P>
He knows Xi'an people through his students. They are not that
sensitive to the fashionable, not that romantic, but
down-to-earth, diligent and talented, he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained a personal episode. At the beginning of 1996 when
he traveled with his wife and daughter from Xi'an to Chengdu by
train, he could only get two tickets because of the unusually
heavy spring traffic.
</P>
<P>
They were stopped by a non-English speaking railway attendant
and none of them could explain to him in Chinese. He was worried,
he said, but a middle-aged couple came up and helped them.
</P>
<P>
More dramatically, that couple did not speak English either but
could find ways to help, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes it is unnecessary to use language in communication,
but the bridge between hearts is more important, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 26 Kenyan Banks Face Merging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Faced with a Central Bank of
Kenya (CBK) deadline within which to improve their capitalization
base or face de-registration, 26 commercial banks and 14
non-banking financial bodies in Kenya are expected to consider
merging.
</P>
<P>
The need to merge was more urgent for the non-banking
financial institutions as none of them presently meets the new
statutory minimum requirement by CBK, experts were quoted by the
Monday's East African weekly as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the June issue of the CBK's Monthly Economic
Review, all commercial banks are required to raise about four
billion Shillings (65 million U.S. Dollars) over the next 18
months. The new rule takes effect toward the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the core of the CBK directive is the large amounts of
non-performing loans granted to customers and institutions.
</P>
<P>
Records indicate that of the total loans amounting to 208.5
billion Shillings (3.5 billion Dollars) advanced to customers, is
a staggering 43.78 billion Shillings (728 million Dollars) up
from 37.9 billion Shillings (627 million Shillings) a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The CBK says currently 15 commercial banks and financial
institutions fail to meet its new minimum capital base
requirements of 200-million-Shilling (3.3 million Dollars) and
150 million Shillings (2.5 million Dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's local banking industry has recently witnessed a number
of mergers as the move toward universal banking gained currency.
</P>
<P>
The 550-million-Shilling (9.3 million Dollars) merger between
National Industrial Credit and African Mercantile Bank or Ambank
is still considered the most notable one yet.
</P>
<P>
Trust Finance Ltd. has merged with Trust Bank Ltd. while
Stanbic Finance has merged with Stanbic Bank Ltd, its parent
company.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Trust Bank Ltd. recorded a decline in profits
before tax of 56 percent from 129 Shillings (2.2 million Dollars)
in 1996 to 57 million Shillings (966,101 Dollars), and a negative
five percent erosion in total assets.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that although profitability is still high in
Kenya's banking sector, only 13 commercial banks have achieved
above the industrial average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xi'an through the Eyes of Foreigners (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- "To see the recent 10 years of
China, go to Shenzhen; to see the past 100 years of China, go to
Shanghai; to see the past 500 years of China, go to Beijing;
and if you want to see the past 2,000 years of this country, you
have to go to Xi'an," said a Norwegian painter when he visited the
city.
</P>
<P>
This ancient city, seat of 12 dynasties in Chinese history and
home to the terra cotta warriors and horses, called by some "the
eighth wonder of the world," is an international tourist
attraction bringing in more than 100,000 visitors every year.
</P>
<P>
As to those foreigners who once lived or worked here, this
northwestern city means much more.
</P>
<P>
Betty F. Coggin, an American professor working with the Xi'an
Institute of Foreign Languages, said her whole family is deeply
connected with this city.
</P>
<P>
Her husband is a college professor in the United States, whose
employer is a sister college of the Xi'an Institute of Foreign
Languages. After a lecture tour here, her husband was so
fascinated by the city that he convinced her to give up her job as
a lawyer to stay with him, too.
</P>
<P>
Coggin said that her son will come to visit her this
summer. And because of his interest in the history and culture of
this city, he will come to Xi'an to teach after his graduation
this year.
</P>
<P>
After one year here, Coggin said she fell in love with the
"night markets" in the city, a Chinatown style bazaar selling
various midnight snacks and refreshments.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an folks are hospitable, she said. She was invited to her
students' homes, attended "funny" marriage ceremonies where brides
and bridegrooms wear western-style dress but do not go to church.
</P>
<P>
In addition, she learned how to cook Chinese food and to make
dumplings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
