<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Round of Rates Hike Feared in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's interest
rates could rise again this week if the volatility in financial
markets, which has caused the Rand to plunge, continues, market
watchers have warned.
</P>
<P>
All big-five banks raised their lending rates by two
percentage points earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Standard Bank, the country's second largest bank, further
increased its prime lending rate by one percentage point to 21.25
percent on Friday and could raise it again this week, depending
on what happened in the markets, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Other banks would not linger on for long before following
suit.
</P>
<P>
Standard Bank's move came after the Reserve Bank increased its
repo rate, the Reserve Bank's lending rate to commercial banks,
by three percentage points to 20.37 percent on Friday. The
Reserve Bank's penalty rate, the marginal lending rate, is now
five percentage points higher at 40.377 percent.
</P>
<P>
The market read the bank's move as a signal that it planned to
make greater use of interest rates and less of the country's
reserves to stabilize the Rand.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Rand lost 10 cents to the Dollar to a record
low of 5.515 and crashed 22 cents against the Pound to 9.2263,
also a record level.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said although the Rand's depreciation would bolster
the price competitiveness of South African exports, it would hit
the information technology sector which relied heavily on
imports.
</P>
<P>
Apart from trimming growth forecasts, the increased interest
rates, with prime at its highest level in 13 years, also meant
delayed investment decisions in the medium term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
