<HEADLINE> China Calls on U.S. to Lift Sanctions, MOFTEC Official Says  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese foreign trade
official expressed the hope that the United States would lift its
sanctions on China and ease or remove its restrictions on
high-tech exports to the country.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference sponsored by the Information Office of the
State Council, Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation Sun Zhenyu said there are still some restrictions on
U.S. high-tech exports to China and, if this problem can be
resolved, bilateral high-tech cooperation is expected to expand.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on U.S. President Bill Clinton's
statement Sunday in an interview with journalists that the
U.S. export restrictions will be considered on a case-by-case
basis under the legal framework, Shi Guangsheng, minister of
foreign trade and economic cooperation, who also attended the
press conference, said that China welcomes any measures taken by
the United States to ease its export restrictions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sun said, President Clinton's visit to China will
create favorable conditions for the development of bilateral
economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the two sides will discuss major economic and
trade issues such as China's entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO), he said. Companies from the two countries
negotiating projects such as airplanes and power stations also are
expected to sign cooperative contracts.
</P>
<P>
Sun spoke highly of U.S. direct investment in China, and said
that the actual U.S.investment in China has exceeded 18 billion
U.S. dollars and opened more than 24,000 joint ventures in China
so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
