<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's Mountainous Villages Accumulating Wealth Through Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Toinzhub, who used to make money
feeding pigs and cows with fruit, has increased her income by
expanding the area of cash trees and by planting hot pepper.
</P>
<P>
Last year, her family made an income of more than 8,000 yuan
(about 960 U.S. dollars) from selling pigs and cows.
</P>
<P>
"Markets have provided us who live in mountainous areas with
broader ways to make money," Toinzhub said.
</P>
<P>
Nang County, where Toinzhub lives, is located on the northern
foot of the Himalayas, more than 3,000 meters above sea level. The
county has quality timber, medicinal herbs such as Chinese
caterpillar fungus, musk and the bulb of fritillary, and many
kinds of fruit such as peaches and apples as well as peppers.
</P>
<P>
Many of these economic resources became rotten or useless in
the past because local farmers and herdsmen had no sense of
turning them into money.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation changed fundamentally in 1994 when the
county established an economic development company, which acted as
agent for local people to sell their produce.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, many local farmers and herdsmen started to sell their
goods at markets in nearby towns and in Lhasa, capital of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Nang County government registered trademarks for its native
produce at the State Administration for Industry and Commerce to
promote sales.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local people have realized the importance of
building roads in a developing market economy. Last year, the
county built 126 kilometers of roads which have connected 85
percent of its villages.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers and herdsmen have also learned to readjust their
farming structure in accordance with changes in the markets.
</P>
<P>
Development of a commodity economy has greatly improved local
people's lives. Statistics show that in 1997 the county's total
industrial and agricultural output value was 41.38 million yuan
(about 4.98 million U.S. dollars), the per capita income of
farmers and herdsmen reached 1,680 yuan (about 202 U.S. dollars),
and the county's revenue amounted to 1.79 million yuan (over
215,670 US dollars) from 220,000 yuan (about 26,506 US dollars) in
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
