<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Russian Trade Structure Undergoing Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The structure of cross-border trade
between China and Russia has shifted from a unilateral form of
bartering to a multilateral development, a senior Chinese official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
At present, Sino-Russian trade covers a variety of forms
including cash transactions, services, and the import and export
of technology and processing, said Hu Chusheng, director of the
European Department of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, during a trade fair held in this capital of northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the ratio of barter between the
two countries has dropped to 20 percent now from 70 percent in the
early 1990s. The amount of cash transactions now makes up half of
the total trade volume.
</P>
<P>
The changes were led by a series of measures taken by the two
governments, said Peng Ruiling, a professor at the Harbin
Polytechnical University.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has turned into a new aspect of Sino-Russian trade in
recent years. Russia has become China's second largest source of
visitors after Japan with the number of visitors to China in 1997
topping 800,000, up 59 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The growth in the number of visitors to China has boosted
China's development in the hotel, restaurant and service
industries.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral import-export structure has also been altered. In
the first five months of this year, China's export of primary
products to Russia decreased sharply while the export of
manufactured goods including hi-tech products increased.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials of the two countries have expressed on many
occasions that they would give priority to the development of
energy, machine-building, space, agriculture, hi-tech and
communications in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
