<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Wastes 1.7 Billion Dollars: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A report issued by a Nairobi
think-tank estimates wasteful spending by the Kenyan government
in the 1995/96 financial year at 107.5 billion Shillings (1.7
billion U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The figure represents 17 percent of the east African country's
gross domestic product (GDP) estimated at 652 billion Shillings
(10.5 billion Dollars), according to the summary of past
Controller and Auditor-General's reports.
</P>
<P>
The summary highlights massive financial mismanagement which
in one year alone deprived the country of enough funds to provide
a 3,500 Shillings (60 Dollars) handout to every Kenyan.
</P>
<P>
Its publishing is expected to complicate Finance Minister
Simeon Nyachae's efforts to renegotiate teachers salaries and
freeze civil service wages to balance the country's budget, the
East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Although cases of abuse of public funds are detailed every
year in the Auditor-General's reports, the analysis provides a
dramatic picture of losses arising from weak financial controls
in 1995/96, and gives comparison with adjacent years and
classifies avenues of waste.
</P>
<P>
The analysis, released last week by the Center for Governance
and Democracy (CDG), an independent non-governmental body, is
likely to embolden opponents of the austerity measures outlined
in this year's budget, among them teachers and bank workers, both
of whom have threatened strike action.
</P>
<P>
The CDG report said public funds were mainly lost through
stalled projects, over-invoicing, revenues not surrendered,
wasteful expenditure, outstanding debts, goods and services paid
for but not delivered, diverted funds and goods released from
bonded warehouses to the local market.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that:
</P>
<P>
-- Governmental financial discipline has declined 300-fold
since the 1993/94 financial year when the auditor-general
questioned wasteful spending of 34.7 billion Shillings.
</P>
<P>
-- Mismanagement has worsened the budget deficit. At the end
of 1992 the government had a small surplus of 1.05 billion
Shillings, which fell to a deficit of 52 billion Shillings in
1993/94 and 56 billion Shillings in 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
-- The 107.5 billion Shillings lost in 1995/96 through waste
is more than half of the entire budget for the current financial
year read two weeks ago. More than half of it is irrecoverable.
</P>
<P>
To balance its 1998/99 budget, the government is seeking to
negotiate a salary increase of up to 200 percent granted to the
teachers last year, which is expected to absorb some 37 percent
of government revenue if fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's budget deficit accounted for 2.7 percent of GDP in the
1997/98 fincial year, according to Nyachae's budget speech
issued on June 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
