<HEADLINE> More Zimbabweans Apply Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Nearly two million of Zimbabwe's
12.5 million people need food aid, The Herald daily reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government has set aside 300 million Zimbabwean Dollars
(15 million U.S. Dollars) for the provision of food aid to people
whose crops failed during the last season because of erratic
rains.
</P>
<P>
Judith Madzorera, acting secretary for public service, labour
and social welfare, told The Herald Sunday that 416,658 people
were currently benefiting from the government's free food
program.
</P>
<P>
This program helps the elderly, the chronically ill and the
disabled, and others who proved to be unable to help themselves,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Those who are able to work to support themselves, but have
been hit by crop failure and who cannot find work, have been
helped under the grain-loan scheme where they borrow grain and
repay after their next harvest.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the grain marketing board urgently needs to import
over 200,000 tons of maize to replenish its strategic grain
reserve stocks by the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, which should always have at least 500,000 tons of
maize, currently holds about 270,000 tons and this will have to
be topped up with imported maize since local supplies are
inadequate to cope with normal demand and all reserve needs.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on Sunday, Chairman of the Grain Marketing
Board Kumbirai Katsande said, "We would prefer that the imports
be effected soonest rather than later. As of now the grain
marketing board has no maize of its own."
</P>
<P>
However, the chairman said he was pleased that funds for the
reserve were being made available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
