<HEADLINE> Jackson Refuses to Coach Chicago Bulls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Phil Jackson has refused an
offer to coach the Chicago Bulls for another year, his attorney
confirmed on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Bulls chairman Jerry Reinsdorf offered him a
chance, Jackson won't return to the Bulls, but he has no future
plans, according to Todd Musberger.
</P>
<P>
"I said no, it's time for me to step away and enjoy some
different things," Jackson told Newsweek magazine in an interview
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Jackson's relations this season with Bulls General Manager
Jerry Krause were strained. The coach billed Chicago's sixth
championship run the "Last Dance," and said his public goodbye at
the Bulls' citywide celebration last week.
</P>
<P>
"For me, it's the perfect conclusion to a wonderful team,"
Jackson said. "There's nothing we can do to top this anymore. Now
it's time to step back from the game for a while."
</P>
<P>
Jackson's departure may effect Michael Jordan's decision.
Jordan has said he won't play for anyone else.
</P>
<P>
Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman also are free agents, as are
six other of the 12 players on the Bulls roster. Pippen said he
would be open-minded to an offer from the Bulls if the other key
members remain.
</P>
<P>
Jackson became Bulls head coach on July 10, 1989. He spent 11
of his 13 NBA seasons as a player with the Knicks and was a member
of their 1973 championship team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
