<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Suspension of E. African Fish to Be Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A suspension on fresh fish
imports imposed by the European Union (EU) on Kenya, Uganda,
Tanzania and Mozambique is likely to be extended beyond the June
30 deadline because of failure to meet EU hygiene requirements.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources say the EU has already decided to extend the
deadline to January next year, though this extension has not been
formally communicated to local fish exporters, the East African
weekly newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The suspension imposed in January this year was to be reviewed
at the end of June if the affected countries invited an EU
inspection team, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is not that bleak. What this means is that
these countries have been given more time to put their house in
order," an official close to EU was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The move will continue to hurt local fishermen, who rely on
the EU to absorb 56 percent of their fish produce. But in the
view of the EU the move is a reprieve for the industry, giving it
more time to meet EU health standards to escape a total ban.
</P>
<P>
The suspension was imposed following EU concern about the
conditions of beaches on Lake Victoria where the fish crop is
collected and also over hygiene standards at processing factories
around the lake.
</P>
<P>
Frozen fish products were later exempted from the ban on
condition they underwent stringent microbiological tests.
</P>
<P>
EU also demanded east African health officials to regularly
inspect the fishing and processing facilities and issue health
compliance certificates.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the local fish industry explain that what has
really been in force, contrary to most press reports, is not a
full-fledged ban, but a tightening of EU health regulations
regarding imports of fresh fish from the region.
</P>
<P>
A key EU demand is that once the fish is pulled out of the
water, it should be put immediately into a clean cold storage.
But most local boats are small and unrefrigerated. Meeting such
criteria would be an expense local fishermen may not easily
afford.
</P>
<P>
The problem started last year when a bacterium called
salmonella was detected in some imported Lake Victoria Nile Perch
in Spain and Italy. EU checks on imported fish from this region
were then tightened.
</P>
<P>
Subsequent reports of cholera in the Lake region only served
to strengthen the EU's demand on local authorities to enforce its
health requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Railways on Brink of Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Railways is on the brink of
collapse because of the dilapidated state the firm is in and it
requires 63 million U.S. Dollars to rehabilitate its
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Monday quoted Lars Jannesson, deputy
managing director of Zambia Railways, as saying at the weekend in
Kitwe, 400 kilometers north of Lusaka, that the state of the
railways' infrastructure is in bad shape due to lack of
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
This is worse especially taking into account the wagons many
of which have been piled without any rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
"The wagons are in very bad shape due to lack of
rehabilitation. This bad state means that you can not run the
rail business anymore," Jannesson said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that his company needs about 63 million
Dollars to rehabilitate the infrastructure such as the tracks and
the wagons. Out of the company's 6,000 fleet of wagons, half of
them are not operational.
</P>
<P>
Jannesson added that the floated staff is another problem in
the running of the company. There are 5,200 permanent workers
and 600 casual employees, but the company intends to reduce its
labour force by 260.
</P>
<P>
According to a 1997 economic report, Zambia Railways' real
output in 1997 amounted to 10 billion Kwacha (seven million
Dollars) as against the output of 12.3 billion Kwacha (8.5
million Dollars) attained in 1996, which was a decline of 18.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
This was the fourth year of persistent decline in output in
the rail transport sub-sector, which indicated serious
operational problems.
</P>
<P>
During the period under review by the report, the company
continued to hold a total stock of 66 locomotive engines out of
which 44 were active, while 22 were not serviceable. The company
also had a total of 75 passenger wagons whose life should be 20
years, but for some reason, they could last only two years.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the company's goods traffic declined by 17.5
percent in 1997 to 1.4 million tons while passenger movement also
declined by 11 percent to 1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
Apart from increased competition from the road transporters,
the poor state of the rail infrastructure and equipment such as
over-aged signaling and telecommunications system and rail track
are the factors for the poor performance of the company, said the
paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
