<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investors Attracted to Buddhist Site at Dunhuang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Dunhuang city, known for its
Buddhist statues, frescoes and valuable manuscripts, has aroused
attention from investors both in China and overseas.
</P>
<P>
Located in northwest China's Gansu Province, the city has long
been sought as a tourism destination. But now, it is becoming a
favorite for domestic and overseas businesses.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang Mountain Villa, for example, is the largest joint
venture between a Hong Kong investment company and the Lanzhou
Guangda Industrial Co. Ltd., involving 100 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A Republic of Korea business and a local enterprise spent 30
million on a packaging assembly line, which is now
operational. The Dunhuang Silk Road Hotel, an 80-million-yuan
cooperative project between a Canadian investment group and the
province's Tourism Bureau, is under construction.
</P>
<P>
The city has approved eight overseas-funded enterprises, with
foreign investment amounting to 180 million yuan, which focus on
tourism-related developments.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it has established twin-city relationship with 14
counties and cities in China and abroad, and opened 24 economic
cooperative projects worth more than 400 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A local official attributed the change to improved
infrastructure, adding that the city has maintained an average
increase of more than 20 percent in its gross domestic product and
revenue in the last five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
