<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Searching for Flying Tiger Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hubei Province is
expected to start another round of work shortly to unearth one of
the Flying Tiger Air Squadron planes which is believed to have
crashed into a lake 54 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The search will be carred out in the Xiafeng Lake in Luojia
Village of Jianli County.
</P>
<P>
The Flying Tigers, led by U.S. Gen. Claire Lee Chennault,
supported the Chinese army and people against the intrusion of the
Japanese troops during World War II.
</P>
<P>
One of the witnesses to the crash, Luo Benhou, now in his 80s,
recalled that on the morning of May 6, 1944, a burning fighter
plane dropped into Xiafeng Lake near his village. He was working
on his paddy fields at the time.
</P>
<P>
He also saw a pilot, who was later saved by a local farmer,
jumping out of the plane.
</P>
<P>
The fighter plane, with the code number 736849, crashed into
the lake after being attacked by Japanese planes.
</P>
<P>
Some reports at that time said the fighter plane exploded
completely.
</P>
<P>
Jianli County has tried several times to excavate the fighter
plane, with a petrol drum, machine gun and bullets already
retrieved.
</P>
<P>
Since there were usually two pilots for each fighter plane, one
pilot is believed missing, according to an analysis by a retired
army commander. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
