<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, HK Sign MOU on Information Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Australian and Hong Kong
officials signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) on
Information Technology here Monday in a bid to boost exchange and
cooperation in the rapidly developing information economy.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Glenys Roper, chief executive of
Australia's Office of Government Information Technology, and K. C.
Kwong, secretary of Hong Kong's Information Technology and
Broadcasting Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The MOU between Australia and the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) was agreed upon last week following
talks between HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa and Australian
Deputy Prime Minister and Trade Minister Tim Fischer in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
The MOU identifies areas of common interest of cooperation
including delivery of government services online, electronic
commerce and Internet applications.
</P>
<P>
Industry investment and technology partnerships, as well as
commercial and industrial exchanges, are also highlighted in the
document.
</P>
<P>
Kwong said many government services were delivered online in
Australia and Hong Kong was considering introducing the electronic
delivery.
</P>
<P>
Asked what the immediate exchange between Hong Kong and
Australia will be in information technology, Kwong said Hong Kong
would encourage business and industrial groups to participate in a
multimedia exhibition in October in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Roper said, "There's a large number of government services
delivered online" in Australia.
</P>
<P>
"For instance, social welfare benefits and information is
delivered online. Tax agents are able to lodge tax returns on
behalf of individuals online, and individuals and companies are
able to apply for information on customs requirements online," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
