<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hanzheng Street: Showcase of China's Private Sector (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China's first private business to be
listed on the stock exchange will probably be selected from those
companies on Hanzheng Street Wuhan, capital of central China's
Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
One candidate is the Wuhan Huayi Group, which recently bought
more than 11 million shares of the state-owned Wuhan Electronic
Industry Group Co., Ltd., and succeeded in having Hanzheng Street
International Co., Ltd. registered in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The group's 36-year-old chairman, Sun Bing, said, "It's high
time for private enterprises to enjoy greater development, and
what I'm most concerned about is how to seize the opportunity."
</P>
<P>
The Huayi Group is only one of 12,743 household-run private
firms along the 500-year-old street, a showcase of the country's
private sector. The street has developed into a modern commercial
and trade center with an area of five square kilometers with
60,000 types of merchandise and a daily flow of 160,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
However, private entrepreneurs on the street are no longer
content with small businesses. Instead, they are turning to real
estate, financial services, infrastructure, and even participation
in reforming the state-owned sector. Now, most of them have come
to realize the limitations of family-based management, and are
trying to transform their businesses into stock or limited
companies.
</P>
<P>
"We should adopt the modern enterprise system in a bid to seek
more rapid development, because the family-centered operation
produces strong human touches, but lacks of science in
decision-making," said Wang Wangsheng, a peddler-turned manager,
who has recruited professionals to his newly established clothing
company.
</P>
<P>
Hanzheng Street has been a living testimonial to the
vicissitudes of China's private business sector, which was
completely wiped out during the Cultural Revolution
(1966-1976). It was not until the late 1970s that the private
sector began to recover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hanzheng Street: Showcase of China's Private Sector (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Local government adopted tax-free and fee-free policies to
encourage jobless people to start small commodity businesses on
the then 1,600-meter street. Long-buried creativity among ordinary
people has since begun to show, as old taboos have been lifted one
after another.
</P>
<P>
The street is best known for its role as the country's first of
its kind to introduce the wholesale system, market-oriented
pricing system, long-distance cargo transportation, and to run a
business in the form of contracts, leasing and mergers.
</P>
<P>
Stalls and dilapidated houses have given way to modern business
buildings, equipped with computerized information centers
providing cargo demand and supply tips and prices. And, at a
nearby cargo service center, a heavy-laden truck leaves for other
parts of China every three minutes.
</P>
<P>
During the past two decades, the sales volume on the street has
been on the rise despite market changes. Last year, its business
volume amounted to 15 billion yuan, more than the total of the
city's top 10 state-owned department stores combined.
</P>
<P>
"The market is fair to every enterprise no matter whether you
are state-owned, collective, or private. We can learn from each
other, and our aim is to seek for common prosperity," said
a senior executive from the street.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses on the street entered a new round of growth
in September when the 15th Party Congress defined clearly that
non-government economies are important components of China's
socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
"Hanzheng Street's history over the past half century has
reflected the process of cognition for the development of China's
private sector," said Professor Wu Xinmu, an economist at Wuhan
University.
</P>
<P>
Now, private businesses are mushrooming across the country. And
every locality is taking measures to boost the sector. Statistics
show that, by the end of last year, China had nearly 30 million
privately run household businesses and larger firms, involving
some 68 million people and 847 billion yuan in annual output
value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petrochemical Base Emerging in East China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The building of this new base will improve the distribution of
the industry, said Yan, since most of China's petrochemical bases
are currently located in the northern or central part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
With rapid economic development, China may need to import oil
from the Middle East and Indonesia to make up its oil
shortages. "With convenient sea transport facilities, Fujian will
surely take the responsibility," Yan said.
</P>
<P>
With the building of this new base, investment from Taiwan and
Southeast Asia is expected to flow in, said Cai Deqi, director of
the Fujian provincial economic development research center.
</P>
<P>
Cai said the development of the petrochemical industry is
expected to boost the growth of chemical fibers, textiles,
plastics and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
A high-ranking official of the province also cited favorable
conditions such as the improved infrastructure and transportation
facilities, and the support from the central government. He said
Premier Zhu Rongji and former Premier Li Peng have endorsed the
plan.
</P>
<P>
To expedite petrochemical development, the province has set up
a special team to supervise the procedure and has adopted
supporting measures, such as setting up corporation groups.
</P>
<P>
Fujian Petrochemical Group is expected to be set up this year
through the merger of three large firms.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the province's petrochemical industrial output was 5.8
billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
