<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petrochemical Base Emerging in East China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A polypropylene project has
recently been put into production at the Fujian Oil Refinery
Corp. (FORC) in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
It is a step for building Fujian into a new petrochemical base,
insiders said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the polypropylene project, which produces 70,000
tons a year, the firm is planing an ethylene project with an
annual output of 600,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The firm, put into operation in 1993, now has an annual oil
refining capacity of four million tons. That figure is expected to
grow to 12 million tons by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"By then, the province will witness the emergence of the
country's sixth largest petrochemical base, following Qilu, Yanshan,
Shanghai, Yangzi and Jinling," predicted Yan Zheng, president of
the provincial Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
According to a plan, the new base under construction will
extend 200 kilometers along the coastline from the Xiaocuo
Economic Development Zone near Meizhou Bay to the Haicang
Investment Zone in Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
Xiaocuo, with FORC as its backbone firm, will be built into a
base for upstream products of the sector. By 2005, the total
investment in this zone is expected to surpass 100 billion yuan,
generating annual industrial output of 100 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Haichang Investment Zone will make the production of
downstream products a priority, such as the organic chemical raw
materials and fine chemical industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
