<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans Fight Loess Plateau Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Financial assistance provided by
the World Bank has enalbed people living on the Loess Plateau in
the northern and northwestern China score remarkable achievements
in curbing heavy erosion.
</P>
<P>
Heavy erosion plagues 450,000 sq.km. on the Loess Plateau, the
most severely eroded area in the nation. The Yellow River carries
over 1.6 billion tons of eroded plateau sand to the sea each
year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, China has invested 2.13 billion yuan, including
World Bank loans of 150 million U.S. dollars, to carry out
anti-erosion programs on 15,000 sq.km., including 13,000
sq.km. subject to heavy erosion.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the anti-erosion project funded by the bank
was completed by the end of 1997 with erosion on some 250,000
ha. effectively brought under control.
</P>
<P>
The total area of controllable land had jumped to 57.8 percent,
up dramatically from the previous 19.3 percent. In addition, the
annual per capita grain output has soared from 381 kg to 543 kg
and farmers' per capita income has jumped from 348 yuan to 756
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The second phase project is expected to use additional World
Bank loans totalling 150 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest TV Producer Enters Digital Technology Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Changhong Electronics Group,
China's largest TV producer, has decided to embrace digital
technology.
</P>
<P>
Digital color TV sets, computers and other telecommunication
products, are expected to be on the market in two or three years.
</P>
<P>
Ni Runfeng, chairman of the board of the Sichuan Province-based
firm, said the group's goal is to squeeze iteself into the "top
500" in the world. He said digital technology has linked the
information industry with electronics.
</P>
<P>
To fulfill its target, the firm has improved its cooperation
with world-famous counterparts. A Changhong research base is also
expected to go into operation.
</P>
<P>
The firm, one of the top 100 in the sector in China
for three consecutive years, produced 6.68 million TV sets last
year, accounting for 35 percent of the total market share. That
figure is expected to increase to 8.5 million, thus taking 45
percent of the market share. 
</P>
</TEXT>
