<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   U.S. Urges Japan to Open Its Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUCHING (Malaysia), June 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States
Monday asked Japan to deregulate and open its economy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. made the appeal at the bilateral meeting between
Japanese International Trade Minister Mitsui Horiuchi and U.S.
Chief Negotiator Charlene Barshefsky before their participation in
the two-day APEC Trade Ministers Meeting which opens here later
Monday, a spokesman of the U.S. delegation said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. reiterated that "Japan must be the engine of growth
for Asia" and in addition to applying fiscal stimulating measures
in dealing with banking sector, Japan should deregulate and open
its economy, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. side said "the APEC ministerial meeting here is a test
of Japan' willingness to do just that." And if Japan opens its
economy in a meaningful way, it will help the economies in the
Asian region.
</P>
<P>
The Unites States will fully participate "in a positive and
constructive manner" in the APEC meeting and is waiting for Japan
to exhibit the same willingness," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The APEC's membership includes Australia, Brunei, Canada,
China, Chinese Taipei, Chile, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, Korea,
Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
