<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke062219 -Bangladesh Economy Recovers from Stagnation: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's economy has
successfully recovered from a stagnation despite of low
investments, imports and external reserves and a high level of
inflation, The Daily Star said Monday quoting a leading economist.
</P>
<P>
"The economy has made a recovery from a two-year stagnation,"
President of the Bangladesh Economic Association, Professor
Wahiduddin Mahmud, told a meeting of the Foreign Investors Chamber
of Commerce and Industries held in Dhaka recently.
</P>
<P>
A sustained agricultural growth, higher exports and industrial
growth helped the economy come out of the stagnation that had kept
a growth rate of 4 percent in the previous years, said Mahmud who
served as a finance and planning adviser to the 1996 caretaker
government.
</P>
<P>
The current over 5 percent GDP (gross domestic product) growth
corresponded to the growth rate in the early 1990s, though it was
far below "our economic potentials", he noted.
</P>
<P>
He endorsed the move to broaden the VAT (value added tax) net
and increase supplementary duty on various products.
</P>
<P>
"Bangladesh's tax-GDP ratio is one of the lowest among the
developing countries," he said, adding that the ratio should be
increased to a standard level of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
"If we want to consolidate our economic strength, there is no
way but to raise the tax-GDP ratio that has stagnated at 12-13
percent since 1992-93," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also strongly criticized some businessmen's tendency to
evade taxes, pointing out that tax evasion "has become a pervasive
practice" in the country.
</P>
<P>
On protection of local industry and a 25 percent cash incentive
for exportable textiles, the professor said there should be a time
limit for such protective measures and incentives so that foreign
investors could make their investment decisions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
