<HEADLINE> Opposition Candidate Wins Colombian Presidential Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Opposition candidate
Andres Pastrana defeated ruling party candidate Horacia Serpa and
won Colombia's presidential run-off election, official from the
National Registry Office said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 97 percent of votes counted, Pastrana collected over
six million, or 480,000 more than his rival.
</P>
<P>
Upon his winning, Pastrana, 44, made a speech, reiterating his
platform promise of peace, reform and more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Serpa conceded defeat later Sunday, calling for his fellow
countrymen's support to the president-elect.
</P>
<P>
In the second ever presidential run-off in Colombian history, a
record turnout of 12.59 million voters was registered.
</P>
<P>
Except for a few armed clashes, the election has been
proceeding in a peaceful way.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana, former mayor of the capital, is a lawyer and
journalist. This is his second bid for the highest office. In
1994's presidential election, Pastrana was narrowly defeated by
the incumbent President Ernesto Samper.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana will be sworn in on August 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
