<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Russia Sign Deal on Nuclear Power Reactors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Ignoring international pressure,
Russia signed an accord with India on Sunday for construction of
two 1,000 mw light water nuclear power reactors in Tamil Nadu, the
southern state of India.
</P>
<P>
The Times of India reported Monday that the accord, which is
supplement to a decade-old agreement with the former Soviet Union,
was signed by visiting Russian Atomic Energy Minister Yevgeni
Adamov and Chairman of Indian Atomic Energy Commission R.
Chidamabaram.
</P>
<P>
The agreement for building two civilian nuclear power plants at
a cost of 2.6 billion U.S. dollars was reached in 1988 between
former Soviet Union President Mikhail Gorbachev and the then
Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
The Times of India said that the accord assumes significance as
it came on the heel of India's nuclear tests last month and showed
that Moscow is willing to cooperate with New Delhi to set up
nuclear power reactors.
</P>
<P>
Adamov arrived here on Sunday via Mumbai and is scheduled to
meet Chidambaram again Monday to give final touches to the
construction of the power plant.
</P>
<P>
Adamov made it clear that Moscow opposed the sanction imposed
by the United States and others following India's nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Ignoring international condemnations for India's nuclear tests
and the sanctions that followed, Russia appeared to find a chance
to strengthen its defense and nuclear cooperations with India, its
traditional ally.
</P>
<P>
Russia agreed last week to sell six advanced 9K81 S300V mobile
air defense systems to India at a cost of billions of U.S. dollars
for deployment at front and army level.
</P>
<P>
An Indian delegation led by Defense secretary Ajit Kumar paid a
six-day visit to Russia last week and as a result, three
Russian-built 1135-6 Krivak class modern frigates ordered last
year by India will be fitted with Indian missile systems.
</P>
<P>
A regular meeting of the joint working group on
military-technical cooperation held in Moscow earlier this month
almost finalized a 10-year defense cooperation program between the
two countries, which will be signed during a scheduled visit by
Russian President Boris Yeltsin to New Delhi in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
