<HEADLINE> Donors to Support Development Projects in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Donors have agreed to support the
development projects in the country's southeastern hill region at
a two-day international conference on "Peace and the Chittagong
Hill Tracts" held here.
</P>
<P>
The conference ended here on Sunday assessed the development
needs in the post-insurgency period to spur growth in the hill
tracts, press reports Monday quoted State Minister for Planning
Mohiuddin Khan Alamgir as saying.
</P>
<P>
Donors' representatives at the conference agreed in principle
to support the initially-assessed 34 long-term development
projects worth 837 million U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We had detailed discussions on six areas," including primary
education, technical and vocational education, health care
facilities, communication, infrastructure and agriculture, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Canada, Australia, and the Netherlands have made commitment to
extending assistance for development activities in the hill
tracts, and the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank have
also shown interest in taking up projects in the region, according
to Economic Relations Division Secretary Mashiur Rahman.
</P>
<P>
The conference, attended by 130 foreign and local peace
campaigners and donors' representatives, was jointly organized by
the Economic Relations Division under the Ministry of Finance and
the United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh government signed a peace agreement with the
hill tribals in December last year, ending decades-long armed
conflict in the Chittagong Hill Tracts with an area of over 14,000
square kilometers, accounting for about 10 percent of the
country's territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
