<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan-funded Enterprises Play Important Role in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan ranks second behind Hong
Kong in investment in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the province had had some 9,300
enterprise funded solely or partially by Taiwan with a total
investment of 13.4 billion US dollars, of which 11.2 billion came
from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Pearl River Delta and the Chaozhou and Shantou region have
attracted the bulk of the investment from Taiwan. Dongguan city at
the delta, for instance, has attracted over 2,300 Taiwan-funded
firms.
</P>
<P>
Lin Qinghui, president of the Shenzhen Taiwan-funded Enterprise
Association, noted that over 70 percent of the Taiwan-funded
enterprises in Shenzhen are operating on a profitable basis. Over
2,400 Taiwan-funded enterprises belong to the association.
</P>
<P>
The focus of Taiwan investments in Guangdong has shifted from
labor-intensive to technology-intensive industries.
</P>
<P>
As part of an effort to reinforce economic and trade
cooperation with Taiwan, Guangdong recently sponsored an
investment discussion and invited over 800 Taiwan businesspeople
to attend it.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Governor Lu Ruihua said the province will introduce a
series of preferential policies to encourage more Taiwan investors
to establish local ventures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
