<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Set up National Hospitals In Districts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka plans to establish a
national hospital in every district in an effort to provide a
better health service throughout the country, according to Health
Ministry sources here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the conversion of a base hospital into a
national hospital would cost 4.62 million U.S. dollars. The funds
from the International Monetary Fund will be utilized for this
project in addition to capital from state coffers.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the government through this project is to serve the
rural areas by providing them with Medical Consultants and modern
medical equipment. This will additionally relieve congestion in
hospitals in Colombo and other major towns, the sources pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
Each national hospital will be fully equipped with special
units such as neuro-surgical, surgical, paediatrics and
gynaecology units.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, a national hospital in Hambantota district
in the deep south and Polonnaruwa district in the North Central
province will be the first to be set up as a pilot project next
month, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
