<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Seeking Ways to Ease Liquidity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from the public
and private sectors met here Monday to form a debt restructuring
committee which will be responsible for improving liquidity and
preventing business collapses.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also try to help settle the debt problems
between creditors and borrowers.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda told reporters that the
committee will consist of members from the Federation of Thai
Industries, the Board of Trade of Thailand and the Thai Bankers
Association.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin and leaders of the three organizations brought up the
idea of setting up the committee at an earlier discussion.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said the committee, to be chaired by Central Bank
Governor Chatumongol Sonakul, will bring together local creditors
and foreign commercial banks, finance companies and financial
institutions to solve the problems of liquidity and debt.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the public-private sectors will review a tax
incentive to be submitted by the Revenue Department, Tarrin said,
adding that the tax measures will be temporary. But he did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
He said all measures, if agreed upon by the committee, will be
sent to the cabinet for approval next week.
</P>
<P>
The debt restructuring should enable banks to begin extending
loans to the manufacturing sector again and stop non-performing
loans from growing, Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the move will help restore foreign
investor confidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
