<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Universities Brace for Modernization Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Preparing for the knowledge
economy era, China is carrying on an ambitious plan to modernize
its outdated colleges and universities in a bid to meet the
challenge of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education announced here today that some 60
universities have been selected in a national program to upgrade
college facilities and improve teaching systems. The program is
being called the "211 Project."
</P>
<P>
The project is the only educational item on a list of state key
construction programs for 1998, which contains 117 items.
</P>
<P>
The plan was drawn up in the mid-1990s by the Chinese
government to build 100 mega-universities which can reach the
heights of universities in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials say that 350 key specialties in the 60
universities will receive funds for renovation, and an educational
computer network and document system will be established to link
universities nationwide.
</P>
<P>
On the list are prestigious institutions of higher learning
universities like Beijing and Qinghua universities, and a large
number of provincial universities.
</P>
<P>
The University of Science of Technology for National Defense
has also been included in the "211 Project."
</P>
<P>
Sources say that these universities have imported more
equipment from overseas and set up advanced laboratories. Some of
them have strengthened themselves through merging with other
universities.
</P>
<P>
China's modern universities appeared in the late 19th century
and adopted the former Soviet Union model in the 1950s. Most of
them are poorly operated and students have no information about
the scientific frontiers, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The country has invested more than 1.3 million yuan (157,000
U.S. dollars) in the project, which is the largest investment in
the educational sector since new China was founded in 1949.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Healthy Sino-U.S. Trade Ties Contribute to Global Economy, Shi Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The sound development of the
Chinese and American economies and the steady growth of bilateral
trade relations have become a contributing factor to a complete
and vibrant global economic system, according to the Chinese trade
minister.
</P>
<P>
Shi Guangsheng, minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, made the remarks at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
According to Shi, China's economic reform program presents
opportunities for furthering the bilateral cooperation. "Both
countries can explore the possibilities in such fields as
enterprise managerial mechanism, infrastructure, housing, social
security and financial supervision system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shi told the press that China in the future plans to put
investment priorities in such sectors as agriculture, forestry,
water conservation, energy, transportation, telecommunications,
environmental protection, high- and new-tech industries and other
infrastructural facilities.
</P>
<P>
China's investment in infrastructure in the next three years
is expected to total 1,100 billion U.S. dollars and the value of
imported goods in the period will reach 600 billions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. firms, based on their advantages and through fair
competition, can work with Chinese businesses for a brilliant
future of the Sino-U.S. economic and trade relations," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"So long as China and the United States bear long-term
benefit in mind and properly handle differences from a strategic
perspective in a constructive manner, the business communities of
both countries will be able to carry out various forms of
cooperation in a stable and relaxed environment," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Shi and Sun Zhenyu, vice trade minister, are scheduled to
answer questions at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 Chinese and overseas journalists attended the
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
