<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Gives U.S. one Month to Settle Textile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is giving the
United States up to early next month to settle its garment trade
row, otherwise the case would be submitted again to the World
Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government's negotiating panel led by the
Garments Textile Exports Board has notified the Philippine party
in Geneva led by Permanent Representative to WTO Ambassador Lilia
Bautista of the position, Manila Bulletin reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva party was also advised to look into the grounds
where the Philippines could file a case against the U.S. by
reviving the unfair trade practice violations of its rules of
origin regulation which took effect in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
Donald Dee, president of the Confederation of Garment Exporters
of the Philippines, said the negotiation bogged down after the
U.S. rejected the proposal of the Philippines to settle for a 10
percent compensation or 50 million U.S. dollar worth of additional
quota.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the U.S. insisted only on a 5 percent
additional quota this year.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the U.S. regulation on Rules of Origin
was the root cause of the garment row between the U.S. and the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Such ruling provides that exports of garments made out of
imported textiles and yarns will only be credited to the quota of
the items' actual country of origin whether or not sufficient
transformation occurred.
</P>
<P>
This rule effectively replaced the previous rule which allowed
mere cutting or lacing of edges of an imported textile already
constituted substantial transformation.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, a major importer of textile for its growing
garment industry of which over 60 percent goes to the U.S. market,
was adversely affected as it now loses some of its valuable
garment quotas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980622.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presale Checks Block Handgun Sales in U.S. Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Justice Department
estimated on Sunday that under the presale checks of the Brady law
some 69,000 handgun sales were blocked in 1997.
</P>
<P>
More than three out of five sales were turned down because the
buyer had a felony conviction or was under felony indictment, the
department's Bureau of Justice Statistics said.
</P>
<P>
The rejections constituted just 2.7 percent of the some 2.6 million
applications nationwide for handgun sales during the year, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Since the Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act took effect in
February 1994, through the end of last year, there have been
242,000 purchases stopped because of the checks, out of a total of
10-plus million purchase applications, the bureau estimated.
</P>
<P>
Felony convictions or indictments for the would-be handgun
buyer accounted for 61.7 percent of the turndowns.
</P>
<P>
The second most frequent reason for denial was domestic
violence, which was responsible for 11.2 percent, including 9.1
percent who had misdemeanor domestic violence convictions and 2.1
percent who were under court orders restraining them from harming
or stalking an intimate partner or child.
</P>
<P>
Another 5.9 percent of the denials were for buyers who turned
out to be fugitives from justice.
</P>
<P>
State law prohibitions blocked sales to 6.1 percent of the
rejectees; drug addiction accounted for 1.6 percent of the
denials; mental illness for 0.9 percent; local law prohibitions
for another 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 11.7 percent of the denials came from all others
barred from handgun purchases under the Federal Gun Control Act of
1968, including illegal aliens, juveniles, dishonorably discharged
servicemen, and people who have renounced U.S. citizenship.
</P>
<P>
The estimates were based on a sampling of the chief law
enforcement officers whose agencies conduct the background checks.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in November of this year, presale checks will be
required for all firearms, not just handguns, purchased from
federally licensed dealers. The dealers will make the checks
through an automated system that Justice Department officials have
said will be operable by that time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
