<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai State Firms Woo Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- An agency was set up recently in
east China's Shanghai municipality to help foreign investors
choose state firms.
</P>
<P>
This indicates local government's encouragement to foreign
investors to cooperate with state firms, economists agreed.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has readjusted its policies on foreign investment,
according to the local government.
</P>
<P>
Under the new policies, foreigners are allowed to purchase,
merge, rent or contract small state businesses. The municipality
also has asked its large state companies to improve cooperation
with their foreign counterparts to speed up technical upgrades and
expand exports.
</P>
<P>
The municipality plans to sell some large state firms to
foreigners, with a total investment of nearly 100 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has provided a list of 100 small and medium-sized
businesses for foreign investors to consider. The firms' total
assets are 744 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Though suffering from poor management and inefficiency, these
state firms have advantages such as intact infrastructures and
skilled workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
