<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Seek Overseas Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The debt-ridden and strike-bound
Philippine Airlines (PAL) will file petitions overseas to seek
protection from foreign creditors, the newspaper Business World
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
PAL officials were quoted as saying earlier that they are
considering the move after a team from Airbus Industry came here
to negotiate terms and possible penalties for the early
termination of aircraft leases and the deferment of purchases.
</P>
<P>
The airline filed last week a massive downsizing program to the
Philippine Securities and Exchange Commission. PAL said its
financial situation was aggravated by the ongoing pilots' strike
which made it unable to pay debts totaling 2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company's 620-member pilots' union went on strike two weeks
ago, demanding revision of its collective bargaining agreement
with the management. The indefinite strike has cost the company
more than 2 billion pesos (50 million dollars) in revenue loss,
PAL said.
</P>
<P>
Under its downsizing plan, PAL plans to reduce its
13,200-strong workforce by nearly 40 percent, dispose 40 of its 54
airplanes, suspends more than two-thirds of its routes and sell
some of its subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
But the Securities and Exchange Commission said over the
weekend that it will not hesitate to order the dissolution of the
airlines if it determines that recovery will take longer than five
years.
</P>
<P>
PAl has given its creditors assurance that it will continue to
pay interest on its loans to commercial banks even during the
course of its rehabilitation program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
