<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0130 GMT, June 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Three rocket-propelled grenades were fired toward
the U.S. embassy in Beirut on Sunday, causing no life and
property losses, the National Broadcast Network radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at 13:00 local time (1000 GMT) when no
diplomats were in the U.S. embassy. The grenades landed only 500
meters away from the embassy on the edge of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese security forces have found part of the time device on
the scene and started investigation. (Lebanon-Explosion-US Embassy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan has refused to open trade with India and
called for settling the core issue of Kashmir between the two
countries first.
</P>
<P>
India had repeatedly requested the Pakistani government for a
free trade between the two countries, while pledging all other
disputes will be taken up afterwards, diplomatic sources was
quoted as saying by the independent News Network International
(NNI) Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Commerce Ministry told NNI that free trade
between Pakistan and India was not feasible, saying that Indian
industries enjoy subsidies and incentives which are not available
to Pakistan's. (Pakistan-India-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Despite U.S. criticism and protests, the Israeli
cabinet Sunday approved a controversial plan to expand Jerusalem's
municipal authority over eight Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which was approved after a five-hour debate in the
cabinet, would create an "umbrella authority" over West Bank
settlements surrounding Jerusalem to the north, south and east.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
have strongly condemned the plan. U.S. officials have described it
as "extremely provocative," saying it could inflame violence in the
region. (Israel-Jerusalem-Expansion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The ambassadors of five European Union (EU) member
nations were recalled for consultations and will leave Belarus for
an indefinite period, British ambassador to Belarus Gessiaca
Pearse said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Polish ambassadors are also to leave.
</P>
<P>
At the end of April, some 20 ambassadors in Minsk were told to
move out of their Drozdy residences because of a forthcoming
overhaul. (Belarus-Ambassadors)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said that his
upcoming visit to China will help deepen the mutual understanding
and expand the cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope in a roundtable discussion here on Friday
with a group of U.S.-based Chinese journalists.
</P>
<P>
"I hope we can expand the areas of cooperation between our
governments and our peoples," the president, who begins his China
tour next Thursday, told the reporters.
</P>
<P>
As home to one-fourth of the world's people and with a rapidly
growing economy, he said, China has enormous contributions to make
to the world of the 21st century. (Clinton-China-Interview)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Leaders of the Burundi government and the
opposition factions agreed Sunday to cease fire in Arusha in
northern Tanzania, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The parties concerned have agreed to a truce not later than
July 20 when the second round of peaceful talks is called up in a
bid to realize the national reconciliation and end years of
bloody conflicts.
</P>
<P>
A joint declaration made by the 17 parties said that six
committees will be established to deal with the problems of
genocide, refugees, peace and public security and others.
(Burundi-Ceasefire)
</P>
