<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Justifies China Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- With only days away from his
trip to China, President Bill Clinton has raised voice to defend
his policy of engagement, warning that isolating that country
would be a disaster for the United States.
</P>
<P>
"In isolating China, we would only encourage China to turn
inward and to act in opposition to our interests and values,"
Clinton wrote in an article published Sunday by Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
The president leaves for China Wednesday for a nine-day visit
which will take him to Xi'an, Beijing, Shanghai, Guilin and Hong
Kong. He will be the first American president to visit China in
almost ten years.
</P>
<P>
He decided to go ahead with the trip despite pressures put on
him by Republicans in Congress to call it off. His critics
criticized the Administration's China policy of engagement as a
policy of appeasement.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters Saturday in the White House that the
substantive changes in China have justified the kind of "measured,
principled engagement strategy we've followed."
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of the roles China played in trying to ease the
tension triggered off by nuclear tests by India and Pakistan and
in stablizing the financial situation in Asia, believing that it
is ever more important to cooperate with China under such
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"The reason I'm going to China now is that I think there have
been a lot of positive changes in the past six years," he said in
interviews with The Los Angeles Times and other news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday the president suggested that permanent most-favored
nation trading status be accorded to China because the annual
battle over the issue on Capitol Hill is counterproductive. "I
don't think this debate every year serves a particularly useful
purpose," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he talked with congressional leaders last year about
ending the annual debate over China's MFN, but no agreement was
reached at that time.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1974 law, renewal of normal trade status with communist
states must be re-approved annually. China has had MFN status
since 1980, and President Clinton extended that again this year
early this month. Congress has 90 days to debate.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Secretary William Daley said on "Fox News Sunday" that
"it's important that we get beyond this year-to-year review by
Congress, and we get into some multiyear, if not permanent" trade
relationship.
</P>
<P>
He said that the "hysteria" it generated was not good for
long-term engagement with a country with a huge market.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton also said that he is disenchanted with the
U.S. sanctions policy, saying in an interview released Saturday
that Washington has become "sanction-happy."
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives passed legislation in May imposing
economic penalties on countries that conduct religious
persecution.
</P>
<P>
The president argued that sanctions can be useful, particularly
when applied by the international community as a whole, but he
said the United States has become too reliant on them as a tool of
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
"The way these sanctions laws are written, they really deprive
the president, any president, of the necessary flexibility in the
country's foreign policy," he told CBS News and the Cox and
McClatchy newspaper chains.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. lawmakers and powerful business lobbies have called
on Congress and the White House to curtail the use of unilateral
sanctions as an instrument of foreign policy. It was reported that
Senate Republican leader Trent Lott and Democratic leader Tom
Daschle plan to appoint a special task force to review the
sanction policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
